ns while touching billing. |\\n| 8 | duplication | `crime_00007` `magic_domain_literal_scatter` | `src/api/plan.ts` | defer | Worth centralizing `\\\"enterprise\\\"`, but do it after billing behavior is clarified to avoid creating the wrong abstraction. |\\n| 9 | IA | `crime_00009` `concept_alias_drift` | `docs/billing.md` | defer | Pick/document canonical tenant terminology, but this is broader product language cleanup. |\\n| 10 | structural | `crime_00010` `large_file` | `src/billing.ts` | defer | The large-file finding will likely improve naturally after extracting `generateInvoice`; avoid a separate split-only refactor first. |\\n\\n**Category Summary**\\n\\n- **Structural:** fix now for `large_function`, direct date usage, misleading refund behavior, comment-only rule, and weak billing test. Defer `large_file` until the billing extraction is done.\\n- **IA:** fix repo-level agent context now; defer concept vocabulary cleanup.\\n- **Duplication:** defer `\\\"enterprise\\\"` literal centralization until the billing model is clearer.\\n- **Frontend:** no top-10 frontend findings.\\n- **Git-history:** no top-10 git-history findings; all shown churn scores are `0`.\\n\\nNo top-10 item looks like an `ignore`. The closest is `large_file`, but it should be treated as a dependent follow-up rather than ignored.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24648,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":902,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":183}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b0b-fcd4-73a2-9c41-3684b3f4a2f4\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: **direct wall-clock reads in billing/date logic**, especially `src/billing.ts` finding `crime_00006`.\\n\\nThe date-boundary flakiness is probably coming from `generateInvoice` reading `Date.now()` / `new Date()` multiple times during one invoice calculation:\\n\\n- `src/billing.ts`: 5× `Date.now()`, 2× `new Date()`\\n- `src/date.ts`: additional direct date usage, mixed UTC/local access, unsafe parsing, and DST-naive day math\\n\\nAt a boundary like midnight, month end, billing-cycle rollover, or DST transition, different calls can observe different effective “days” or interpret them differently. The highest-risk supporting clue is `src/date.ts` finding `crime_00003`: the same date receiver mixes UTC and local methods, so behavior can change by host timezone.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n1. Inject a clock into billing/domain code instead of calling `Date.now()` or `new Date()` directly.\\n2. Capture `now` once at the start of `generateInvoice`.\\n3. Use one date family consistently, preferably UTC for billing calculations.\\n4. Update tests to pass a fixed boundary timestamp.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // all billing-cycle, due-date, and invoice-date logic derives from `now`\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen test the edge case with a pinned instant:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-03-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n\\nexpect(invoice.billingPeriodStart).toBe(\\\"...\\\");\\n```\\n\\nI would fix `src/billing.ts` first, because it directly owns invoice generation and has repeated runtime clock reads inside a large function. Then audit the helpers in `src/date.ts` for UTC/local mixing and timezone-unsafe parsing, since those can keep the boundary bug alive even after the billing clock is injected.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":26069,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":486,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":36}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e39f3-16f3-7dd3-a392-072408a15c31\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `direct_date` in [src/billing.ts](src/billing.ts), especially inside the large `generateInvoice` function.\\n\\nThe scan shows 7 direct wall-clock reads:\\n\\n```text\\n5x Date.now(), 2x new Date()\\nlines: 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273\\n```\\n\\nFor a date-boundary billing failure, that is the strongest signal. If invoice period, due date, proration, grace-period, or renewal logic calls `Date.now()` / `new Date()` internally, tests can pass or fail depending on when they run: midnight, month end, DST shifts, timezone offsets, or year boundaries.\\n\\nThe high-risk `large_function` finding makes this worse because `generateInvoice` is 204 lines long, so date reads may be spread across unrelated billing responsibilities. One branch might calculate the billing period from one clock read while another branch calculates due dates from a later clock read.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // Use `now` everywhere in this invoice generation path.\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen update tests to pass a fixed instant:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nKey rule: capture `now` once at the boundary of invoice generation and thread that value through all date calculations. Avoid repeated `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls inside domain logic. That makes the edge case reproducible and removes wall-time flakiness from billing tests.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":417,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":28}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## What `src/billing.ts` does\n\nIt's a 310-line domain module centred on **`generateInvoice`** (204 lines, lines 50–253) plus a misleadingly-named **`calculateRefundPreview`** (lines 40–44) that actually performs side effects (`saveRefundAudit`, `sendRefundEmail`). The file declares 5 top-level functions and works heavily with the `\"enterprise\"` plan concept and wall-clock time (7 direct `Date.now()`/`new Date()` calls).\n\n## Files I'd also need to read\n\n- **`src/date.ts`** — billing's date helpers live here, and the scan flags it as the epicentre of temporal bugs (UTC/local mixing, unsafe `new Date(\"…\")` parses, DST-naive `+86400000` math, host-locale drift). Anything `generateInvoice` does with dates is probably routed through this file.\n- **`src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts`** — all three repeat the `\"enterprise\"` literal (crime_00009). Plan policy is duplicated across them; editing billing without checking these risks divergent policy.\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** — exists but the suite is hollow: one test has zero assertions (crime_00008), another only uses weak matchers (crime_00021). Don't trust green tests here.\n- **Whatever defines `saveRefundAudit` / `sendRefundEmail` and the owner/billing-support permission check** — the comment at line 39 encodes a rule (\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\") that the surrounding code doesn't obviously implement (crime_00014).\n\n## Risks flagged for `src/billing.ts`\n\n| Severity | Charge | Where | Why it matters for an editor |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **high** | God Function | `generateInvoice` L50–253 (204 lines, 3.4× threshold) | Mixed responsibilities — an edit in one section likely interacts with code you didn't load. |\n| medium | Temporal Recklessness | 7× `Date.now()`/`new Date()` at L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 | Non-deterministic; tests can't pin a fixed moment. |\n| medium | False Identity | `calculateRefundPreview` L40–44 | \"Preview\" name but performs audit + email side effects — callers may assume purity. |\n| medium | God File | whole file, 310 LOC | At threshold; hidden local coupling. |\n| medium | Logic in the Alibi | comment at L39 | Refund authorisation rule lives only in prose. |\n| low | Unfinished Business | 4 markers L183–308 (FIXME/HACK/XXX/TODO) | Hard to tell which logic is load-bearing. |\n\nPlus the cross-cutting hits that touch billing: the scattered `\"enterprise\"` literal (crime_00009) and the absence of any `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` (crime_00004) — meaning conventions aren't discoverable before editing.\n\n**Before editing**: read `src/date.ts` and the three `\"enterprise\"`-referencing files alongside `billing.ts`, treat the existing tests as non-protective, and clarify the owner/billing-support refund rule from L39 before touching `calculateRefundPreview` or any refund path inside `generateInvoice`.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## What `src/billing.ts` does\n\nIt's the billing domain module. Two functions are named in findings:\n- `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253) — a 204-line invoice generator that reads the wall clock heavily (`Date.now()`/`new Date()` at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273).\n- `calculateRefundPreview` (lines 40–44) — name implies a pure calculation but it calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`, so it actually performs side effects.\n\nThe file also encodes (or rather, *doesn't* encode) a permission rule via comment on line 39: *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* — the domain terms `owner`, `plan`, `billing` aren't visible nearby in code, so the rule is prose-only. It special-cases the `\"enterprise\"` plan as a bare string literal (line 7). 5 top-level functions, 310 lines total.\n\n## Files I'd also want to read before editing\n\n| File | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `src/billing.test.ts` | Two weak tests cover this module — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` (lines 4–6, zero asserts) and `\"creates an invoice\"` (lines 8–10, weak matchers). I can't trust either to catch regressions. |\n| `src/date.ts` | Likely the intended clock/date helper (also flagged for direct `Date` use). If I'm adding logic, this is where a `now()` abstraction would land. |\n| `src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts` | All four files (incl. billing.ts) hardcode `\"enterprise\"`. Changing plan logic here likely needs coordinated edits there. |\n| `docs/billing.md` | Concept-alias drift: docs mix `tenant`/`account`/`organisation`/`team`/`workspace`. Worth checking which term the billing code is supposed to align with. |\n\n## Risks the scan flagged for `src/billing.ts`\n\n| Severity | Charge | Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| **high** | God Function (`generateInvoice`, 204 lines, 3.4× threshold) | Sections likely mix responsibilities; localized edits can miss cross-section effects. |\n| medium | Temporal Recklessness (7 direct `Date` calls) | Non-deterministic; tests can't pin time without monkey-patching. |\n| medium | String Sprinkles (`\"enterprise\"` in 4 files) | Plan-tier policy duplicated. |\n| medium | False Identity (`calculateRefundPreview` does side effects) | Callers may treat as pure. |\n| medium | God File (310 lines, just over threshold) | Hidden local coupling. |\n| medium | Logic in the Alibi (line 39 comment-rule) | Refund authorization rule lives in prose, not code. |\n| low | Unfinished Business (4 TODO/FIXME/HACK/XXX between lines 183–308) | Unclear which behaviour is load-bearing. |\n\nRepo-wide context worth knowing before editing: **no `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`/skills file** (Missing Agent Context, medium), so any conventions I follow have to be inferred from the code itself.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/codex/refactor-08-architecture.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b11-561a-7b71-b862-1f4ec4feff69\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The scan has two architecture/package-surface findings relevant to this refactor:\\n\\n1. `crime_00002` — `layer_violation`\\n   - File: `src/domain/billing.ts`\\n   - Bad edge: `src/domain/billing.ts` imports `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`\\n   - Rule violated: `domain cannotImport presentation`\\n\\n2. `crime_00003` — `deep_import`\\n   - File: `src/application/billing-flow.ts`\\n   - Bad edge: imports `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`\\n   - Problem: reaches past `some-pkg`’s published public surface into private internals.\\n\\nRecommended refactor:\\n\\n- Break the import from `src/domain/billing.ts` to `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`.\\n  Tie-in: fixes `crime_00002` and likely helps break the circular dependency in `crime_00001`.\\n\\n  The domain layer should not know how invoices are rendered. If `billing.ts` needs something from presentation, that dependency should be inverted. Put a domain-owned interface or value type in `src/domain`, for example:\\n\\n  ```ts\\n  export interface InvoicePresenter {\\n    renderInvoice(invoice: Invoice): string;\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  Then `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` can implement or adapt to that interface, while application code wires them together. The dependency direction becomes:\\n\\n  ```text\\n  domain <- application -> presentation\\n  ```\\n\\n  instead of:\\n\\n  ```text\\n  domain -> presentation\\n  ```\\n\\n- Redirect `src/application/billing-flow.ts` away from `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`.\\n  Tie-in: fixes `crime_00003`.\\n\\n  Prefer the package’s public entry point, for example:\\n\\n  ```ts\\n  import { helper } from \\\"some-pkg\\\";\\n  ```\\n\\n  If the helper is not publicly exported, do not keep the deep import as a shortcut. Wrap the needed behavior behind an application-owned interface and implementation, or replace it with supported public API behavior. If this is truly missing upstream functionality, the right long-term move is an upstream export/request, not coupling to `dist/internal/private`.\\n\\nHow the risks differ:\\n\\n- `layer_violation` is architecture risk. It tells an agent that changing one layer may unintentionally require knowledge of another layer’s responsibilities. Here, domain depending on presentation inverts the intended direction of change and contributes to the 3-file cycle involving `billing-flow.ts`, `billing.ts`, and `invoice-view.ts`.\\n\\n- `deep_import` is package-boundary risk. It may work today, but it depends on private file layout inside a dependency. An agent may assume the import is stable because TypeScript resolves it, but an upgrade or rebuild of `some-pkg` can silently remove or move that path.\\n\\nSo: break the domain-to-presentation import through a domain-owned interface, and redirect the package deep import through `some-pkg`’s public API or a local adapter.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":18281,\"cached_input_tokens\":11136,\"output_tokens\":651,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":38}}\n",
