/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e396e-a878-71e1-87ae-c89f67676d30\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `crime_00004` / `direct_date` in [src/billing.ts](/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/fixtures/01-messy-ts-app/src/billing.ts).\\n\\nThe scan shows `generateInvoice` reads wall-clock time directly in several places: `Date.now()` / `new Date()` on lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`. For a date-boundary billing failure, that is the strongest explanation: the invoice logic can observe different “now” values during one call, or tests can cross midnight/month-end/timezone boundaries while running. The large `generateInvoice` function makes that worse because date policy is mixed into a 204-line domain function.\\n\\nProposed fix: inject a single clock value into billing logic and derive all billing dates from it.\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere in this invoice calculation\\n  // avoid Date.now() / new Date() inside the function body\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen update the failing edge-case test to pass a fixed date near the boundary, for example month-end or UTC midnight:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-02-28T23:59:59.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n\\nexpect(invoice.periodEnd).toEqual(/* expected deterministic date */);\\n```\\n\\nIf this were a real patch, I would also add one regression test for the exact boundary that failed and replace every direct date read inside `generateInvoice` with the single injected `now`. That keeps the fix sc