/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e390a-1226-7b63-894c-41084016eb6a\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `crime_00004` in `src/billing.ts` - direct wall-clock reads inside billing logic.\\n\\nThe scan found `5x Date.now()` and `2x new Date()` in `src/billing.ts`, including inside the large `generateInvoice` function. For a date-boundary flaky test, that is the strongest signal: invoice behavior is probably being computed from the actual system time, so tests can pass or fail depending on whether they run near midnight, month-end, timezone transitions, or billing-period rollover.\\n\\nThe high-risk `generateInvoice` finding makes this worse because date logic is buried inside a 204-line function, so one part may read “now” while another later branch reads it again and crosses a boundary.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere in this invoice generation path\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen update tests to pass a fixed clock:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-31T23:59:59.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\ngenerateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nKey detail: capture `now` once per invoice generation and thread that value through all billing-period/date calculations. Avoid mixing multiple `Date.now()` calls in one run, because even an injected clock can still reproduce boundary drift if the function asks for time repeatedly.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":361,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":30}}\n