/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# PR review verdict\n\n**Headline:** 1 BLOCK, 8 WARN, 13 IGNORE. The blocker is a 204-line refund/invoice function; everything else is fixable in follow-up.\n\n---\n\n## 🛑 BLOCK MERGE (1)\n\n### `crime_00001` — God Function `generateInvoice`\n- **Why:** severity=high (0.9), agent_risk=0.63, confidence=0.95. 204 lines is 3.4× the domain threshold and this is **billing/invoicing** code — the highest-blast-radius area in the repo. Combined with `crime_00004` (7× wall-clock reads in the same file) and `crime_00011` (rule-bearing comment about refund auth), any agent editing one part of `generateInvoice` is statistically going to miss interactions in another.\n- **Ask before merge:** extract cohesive sections into named helpers. This is the one finding where the cost of letting it in is real future regressions, not just code-smell debt.\n\n---\n\n## ⚠️ WARN (8) — fix in follow-up PRs, don't block this one\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev / agent_risk | Why warn (not ignore) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00008` | False Identity — `calculateRefundPreview` does side effects | 0.55 / 0.52 | Misleading name in a **refund** flow. `agent_risk` understates this — a name that lies in payments code is a category of bug worth surfacing loudly. Borderline-block; if the side effects include `sendRefundEmail` to real users, escalate. |\n| `crime_00002` | Missing Agent Context | 0.6 / 0.61 | Meta finding — won't break this PR, but every future PR is riskier without an AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md. Worth a tracked ticket. |\n| `crime_00005` | Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` | 0.6 / 0.61 | 5 wall-clock reads in a module literally called `date.ts` — that's the abstraction layer that should *fix* this, not propagate it. |\n| `crime_00004` | Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` | 0.6 / 0.53 | 7 raw `Date.now()`/`new Date()` calls in domain code makes the invoicing logic non-deterministic in tests. Pairs with the `generateInvoice` block — fix together. |\n| `crime_00007` | String Sprinkles — `\"enterprise\"` in 4 areas | 0.5 / 0.6 | The literal has already escaped into UI, jobs, API, and billing. One more PR and it'll be policy-by-grep. Centralise before the next plan-type lands. |\n| `crime_00009` | Concept Alias Drift — tenant/account/org/team/workspace | 0.55 / 0.58 | 4 aliases × 5 files. Real duplication risk but resolution is a design conversation, not a blocker. |\n| `crime_00012` + `crime_00014` | Duplicated Nav Source + Route Metadata Drift | 0.6 / 0.57, 0.6 / 0.56 | Same destination (`/settings/billing`) labelled 4 ways. These are one bug — fix in one PR. |\n| `crime_00011` | Logic in the Alibi — refund auth rule lives in a comment | 0.5 / 0.5 | \"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\" is **load-bearing policy** sitting in prose. Encode it as a guard. Borderline-block if the comment is actually the only spec for that rule. |\n\n**Notable exclusions from warn:**\n- `crime_00006` (test with 0 asserts) — confidence is 0.88, but severity is only 0.45 and `test_gap=0`. Worth flagging in PR comments; deleting/asserting it is a 30-second fix. Calling this WARN rather than BLOCK because a single empty test isn't load-bearing.\n- `crime_00010` (large_file billing.ts 310 lines) — barely over threshold (1.0×). The `generateInvoice` block already covers the underlying problem.\n- `crime_00013` (TODO density in `src/todo.ts`) — the filename is `todo.ts`, so this might be by design / a fixture artefact. Either way, low blast radius.\n\n---\n\n## 💤 IGNORE (13) — note in passing, don't gate the merge\n\nAll have severity ≤ 0.4 **and** agent_risk ≤ 0.51:\n\n- `crime_00010`, `crime_00013` — covered above; bundled with their bigger relatives.\n- `crime_00015` — broken doc link to `./setup.md`. Cheap fix, but not a merge gate.\n- `crime_00016` — weakly-asserted test. Less severe than `crime_00006`.\n- `crime_00017`, `crime_00018`