/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to reduce risk in `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Break up `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253)\n**Finding:** `crime_00001` — God Function, severity high, agent_risk 0.63.\n\n204 lines is 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold, and it's the single highest-risk finding in the scan. A function this size almost certainly mixes unrelated responsibilities — pricing, tax, proration, persistence, formatting — and is the main reason `src/billing.ts` itself crosses the 300-line `God File` threshold (`crime_00010`). Extracting cohesive sections into named helpers shrinks the surface an agent has to reason about per edit, and it's a prerequisite for almost every other fix below — you can't usefully inject a clock or rename a side-effectful function while it's buried inside a 200-line body.\n\n## 2. Inject a clock to kill the 7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls\n**Finding:** `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness, lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273.\n\nSeven separate wall-clock reads in domain code means every test that touches billing has to either run at wall time or monkey-patch globals. Combined with the weak/empty tests next door in `src/billing.test.ts` (`crime_00006`: zero asserts; `crime_00016`: weak matchers), this file currently has *both* non-deterministic logic *and* tests that wouldn't catch a regression anyway. Threading a `Clock` / `now()` abstraction through the extracted helpers from change #1 is what makes meaningful assertions possible.\n\n## 3. Fix the refund pair: rename `calculateRefundPreview` and encode its hidden rule\n**Findings:** `crime_00008` (False Identity, lines 40–44) + `crime_00011` (Logic in the Alibi, line 39, directly above it).\n\nThese are adjacent and the same defect viewed from two angles: a function named like a pure calculator (`calculateRefundPreview`) that actually calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`, sitting under a comment that quietly declares the policy *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\"* An agent reading the name will treat it as safe to call from a render path; an agent skimming the body will miss the comment's authorization rule entirely. Split the pure preview from the side effect, encode the owner/support check as a named guard returning a typed result, and delete the comment in favour of the guard's name. Bonus: the \"enterprise\" literal in the same area is part of the cross-file scatter in `crime_00007` — lifting it to a constant while you're here removes one more place the policy can drift.\n\n---\n\nDeliberately skipped from billing.ts: the file-level God File (`crime_00010`) resolves naturally once #1 lands, and the 4 in-file TODOs (`crime_00020`) are low-severity noise compared to the structural issues above.",
