/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Most likely cause\n\n**`crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`** (lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273).\n\n`generateInvoice` reads the system clock 7 times directly (`Date.now()` ×5, `new Date()` ×2). On a date-boundary test, each call observes wall time at the moment it runs, so:\n\n- Two calls inside the same invoice can straddle midnight/month-end and disagree about \"today\", producing inconsistent due dates, proration windows, or period labels.\n- Tests can't pin a fixed moment without monkey-patching globals — anything that does work is order- and machine-dependent.\n\nThis is amplified by two neighbouring findings:\n\n- **`crime_00001` (God Function)** — `generateInvoice` is 204 lines mixing responsibilities, so the multiple clock reads are scattered through unrelated branches and easy to miss.\n- **`crime_00006` (Test That Proves Nothing)** — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has 0 assertions, so the test suite isn't actually catching the boundary case; it's just executing the path. The flakiness is probably surfacing in a sibling test that *does* assert, while this one silently passes.\n\n`crime_00005` (same pattern in `src/date.ts`) suggests there's already a date module that *should* be the choke point — but `billing.ts` is bypassing it and reading the clock inline.\n\n# Proposed fix\n\n1. **Inject a clock.** Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): Date`) and thread it through `generateInvoice` (constructor injection or a `{ now }` option, depending on how the module is consumed). Replace all 7 inline reads with a single `const now = clock.now()` captured once at the top of the function — that alone removes the straddle-midnight class of bug, even before tests change.\n2. **Route through `src/date.ts`.** Fix the same pattern there (`crime_00005`) so the date module is the only place that touches `Date` directly, and have `billing.ts` consume it.\n3. **Pin time in the failing test.** Use `vi.useFakeTimers()` / `vi.setSystemTime(...)` (Vitest is the stack) to reproduce the boundary deterministically, then add a real assertion to the empty `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` test so the boundary case is actually guarded going forward.\n4. **Don't refactor the God Function in the same change.** `crime_00001` is real but orthogonal — extracting helpers while also changing time semantics will make the bisect harder. Land the clock fix first, then split the function.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## PR Review: 01-messy-ts-app\n\nCategorising 22 findings against an empty baseline. Cutoffs: **block** when severity ≥ 0.85 *or* a single finding combines a real correctness risk with a high agent_risk; **warn** for medium-severity issues an agent could plausibly compound on the next edit; **ignore** for low-severity style noise (still worth fixing eventually, not worth blocking the merge).\n\n### Block merge (1)\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev | agent_risk | Why block |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00001 | God Function (`generateInvoice`, 204 lines) | 0.9 | 0.63 | High severity *and* the function is in the billing path. 3.4× the domain threshold, mixed responsibilities → next agent edit will silently miss interactions. Extract before any further change lands. |\n\n### Warn (13)\n\nThese are real concerns but landable if tracked. Most cluster around two themes: **agents will be misled by this code** and **multiple-source-of-truth drift**.\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev / agent_risk | Why warn (not block) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00008 | False Identity (`calculateRefundPreview` has 3 side-effect signals: `saveRefundAudit`, `sendRefundEmail`) | 0.55 / 0.52 | The closest call to \"block\" — a name lying about side effects is exactly the trap `crimes` is built to surface. Borderline; flag it loudly in the PR. |\n| crime_00002 | Missing Agent Context (no AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md/SKILL.md) | 0.6 / 0.61 | Cheap fix, big agent payoff. Worth doing now but won't break anything if it slips. |\n| crime_00004 | Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` (7× clock reads) | 0.6 / 0.53 | Wall-clock in domain code = flaky tests + monkey-patching. Inject a clock. |\n| crime_00005 | Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (5× clock reads) | 0.6 / 0.61 | Same problem; `test_gap=1` (no tests) raises agent_risk further. |\n| crime_00007 | String Sprinkles (\"enterprise\" across 4 files / 4 areas) | 0.5 / 0.6 | One more copy lands and it's duplicated policy. Centralise before the next edit. |\n| crime_00009 | Concept Alias Drift (tenant/account/org/team/workspace across 5 files) | 0.55 / 0.58 | An agent extending one vocabulary will duplicate logic that already exists under another name. |\n| crime_00010 | God File (`billing.ts` 310 lines) | 0.6 / 0.5 | Same file as crime_00001 — fixing the God Function will likely shrink this naturally. |\n| crime_00011 | Logic in Comments (\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\") | 0.5 / 0.5 | Hidden prose rule on a refund path. Encode it as a guard or test. |\n| crime_00012 | Duplicated Navigation Source (`/settings/billing`: \"Plans\" vs \"Billing\") | 0.6 / 0.57 | Pair this with crime_00014 — same destination, multiple labels. Fix once. |\n| crime_00013 | TODO density in `src/todo.ts` (14 markers, 424/1k LOC) | 0.4 / 0.57 | The file *is* TODOs. Either it's a deliberate parking lot (move to issue tracker) or it shouldn't ship. |\n| crime_00014 | Route Metadata Drift (`/settings/billing` labelled 4 different ways) | 0.6 / 0.56 | Sibling to crime_00012 — align route + nav + page title in one pass. |\n| crime_00015 | Docs-Code Drift (`docs/teams.md` → missing `./setup.md`) | 0.35 / 0.51 | Low severity but `agent_risk > 0.5` because `test_gap=1` — agents will follow the stale link. Trivial to fix. |\n| crime_00006 | Test That Proves Nothing (\"renders the enterprise plan\", 0 asserts) | 0.45 / 0.46 | A green test with no assertion lies to humans *and* agents about what's covered. Borderline-block; warn because deleting it is acceptable. |\n\n### Ignore (8)\n\nLow severity, low agent_risk, or duplicates of warnings already flagged. Not worth blocking the PR — file as cleanup or leave for `crimes scan --all` later.\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev / agent_risk | Why ignore |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| crime_00016 | Weak test (\"creates an invoice\", weak matcher) | 0.25 / 0.34 | Lowest agent_risk in the report. Worth strengthening but not a merge gate. |\n| crime_00017 | Option Bag Junk Drawer (`describeCheckout` reads 6 props off generic `options`) | 0.3 / 0.48 | Style-shaped; agent_risk under 0.5. Name the shape next time you touch it. |\n| crime_00018 | Return Shape Roulette (`resolvePaymentResult`, 3 shapes, 0% key overlap) | 0.3 / 0.48 | Same module as 00017, same vibe. Annotate the return type when convenient. |\n| crime_00019 | Negative Flag Maze (`!disableBilling && !skipRetry`) | 0.25 / 0.47 | Local readability nit. |\n| crime_00020 | TODO density in `billing.ts` (4 markers, 12.9/1k LOC) | 0.2 / 0.4 | Already covered by the God File / God Function warnings — fixing those clears most of these. |\n| crime_00021 | Orphaned `/account/subscription` | 0.4 / 0.46 | The three orphan routes are below the warn bar individually. But: |\n| crime_00022 | Orphaned `/team` | 0.4 / 0.46 | …they're the same three files that drove crime_00009 (alias drift). |\n| crime_00023 | Orphaned `/workspace/members` | 0.4 / 0.46 | If the alias-drift cleanup picks a canonical term, two of these three routes should be deleted as part of it. Track there. |\n\n### One-line PR verdict\n\n**Request changes.** Block on crime_00001 (God Function in billing). The 13 warnings cluster into three cleanup passes — extract billing, pick canonical names (enterprise / tenant / `/settings/billing`), inject a clock — and the 8 ignores mostly fall out for free once those land.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 risk-reducers for `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Extract `generateInvoice` into named helpers (crime_00001 — God Function)\n- 204 lines (50–253), 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold, severity 0.9.\n- This is the single biggest agent-risk surface in the file: it almost certainly mixes pricing, proration, tax, persistence, and side effects, so any agent editing one branch will load incomplete context for the rest.\n- It also subsumes other findings: the 7 wall-clock reads (crime_00004) and the 4 TODOs (crime_00020) are scattered through this function (lines 57–273 / 183–308). Splitting first makes them addressable in isolation, and the file drops below the 300-line God File threshold (crime_00010) as a free side effect.\n\n## 2. Split or rename `calculateRefundPreview` + encode the comment rule (crime_00008 + crime_00011)\n- The name suggests a pure preview, but the body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` (lines 40–44). An agent will reuse it expecting no I/O and double-fire an audit/email.\n- Directly above it (line 39) sits the un-encoded rule: *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\"* Crimes flags this as Logic in the Alibi because the surrounding code doesn't reference `owner`, `plan`, or `billing` — the authorization gate lives only in prose.\n- Fix together: extract the pure calculation (`previewRefundAmount`) from the side-effecting `processRefund`, and turn the comment into a named guard (`canRefundEnterprisePlan(actor, plan)`) with a test. Pairing them is what closes the loop — renaming alone leaves the rule unenforced.\n\n## 3. Inject a clock to kill Temporal Recklessness (crime_00004)\n- 7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` reads at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 — billing code reading wall time is the textbook case where tests have to monkey-patch `Date` to pin invoice dates, due dates, and proration boundaries.\n- Replace with a `Clock` (or `now: () => number`) passed into the module/function. Cheap to do, makes every invoice path deterministic, and removes the \"tests couple to wall time\" failure mode that `test_gap: 0.5` is already hinting at.\n\n---\n\nDeliberately left out: the `\"enterprise\"` literal sprinkle (crime_00007) is real but cross-cutting across 4 files — better tackled as part of a plan/registry consolidation, not inside billing.ts. And the God File finding (crime_00010) resolves itself once #1 lands.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Most likely cause: Temporal Recklessness in `generateInvoice`\n\nThe smoking gun is **crime_00004**: `src/billing.ts` has **7 direct reads of the system clock** (`5× Date.now()`, `2× new Date()`) at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 — all inside the 204-line `generateInvoice` body (crime_00001, lines 50–253). Every one of those calls observes wall time at runtime, so the function's output depends on *when* it executes. That is exactly the shape of a date-boundary flake: tests pass at 14:00 and fail at 23:59:59 when one of those reads lands on the next day/month/year.\n\nCompounding factors from the same scan:\n\n- **crime_00005**: `src/date.ts` has another 5 direct clock reads — likely the helpers `billing.ts` calls, so swapping just the billing call sites won't fully fix it.\n- **crime_00006**: `renders the enterprise plan` test has zero assertions. Whatever it was meant to pin down at the boundary, it isn't pinning. False green.\n- **crime_00001 + crime_00010**: God Function + God File. The 7 clock reads are scattered across 200+ lines, so any \"just freeze time around this block\" fix will be fragile.\n\nThe lower-ranked findings (alias drift, nav drift, orphaned routes, option bags) don't plausibly cause time-boundary flakiness — ignore them for this bug.\n\n# Proposed fix\n\n1. **Introduce a `Clock` seam.** Add `interface Clock { now(): number }` and a default `systemClock`. Replace every `Date.now()` / `new Date()` in `src/billing.ts` *and* `src/date.ts` with `clock.now()` / `new Date(clock.now())`. Thread `clock` through `generateInvoice` (and the `src/date.ts` helpers) as a parameter with a default of `systemClock` so production callers don't change.\n2. **Pin the clock in tests.** In `src/billing.test.ts`, construct a `FakeClock` set to a known instant (and add cases at the suspect boundaries: end-of-day UTC, end-of-month, year rollover, DST transition if billing localizes).\n3. **Fix the empty test (crime_00006)** — `renders the enterprise plan` at lines 4–6 has no `expect`. Either assert the boundary behaviour it was meant to protect or delete it; right now it's hiding the regression.\n4. **Don't refactor the God Function yet.** crime_00001 is real but orthogonal — extracting helpers while chasing a flake risks moving the bug. Land the clock seam + tests first, then split `generateInvoice` in a separate commit.\n\nThe crimes scan can't tell you *which* of the 7 clock reads produced today's failure, but it tells you the whole class is non-deterministic — so the right fix is the seam, not patching one call site.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:88:        "reasoning": "The agent proposes introducing a Clock seam: 'interface Clock { now(): number }' with a default systemClock, threading it through generateInvoice as a parameter, and using a FakeClock in tests. This is a textbook dependency-injection abstraction — no mention of monkey-patching globals, sinon fake timers, or overriding Date.now directly. The fix correctly addresses both billing.ts and the helpers in date.ts, and properly defers the orthogonal God Function refactor."
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-judge/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Triage plan — top 10 findings\n\n**Bucket coverage:** the strict top 10 (by severity → agent_risk) is **8 structural + 2 duplication**. There are **no git-history findings** (every `churn` is 0 — this fixture has no git signal yet), **no IA or frontend findings** in the top 10. The first IA findings are at #11 (`crime_00012` duplicated nav source) and #13 (`crime_00014` route metadata drift); call them out if you want a broader sweep.\n\n## Structural (8)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | File | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `crime_00001` | God Function `generateInvoice` | `src/billing.ts:50–253` | **Fix now** — 204-line function is the highest-risk item; the surrounding cleanups (clock injection, comment-rule, file split) all become easier once it's broken up. |\n| 2 | `crime_00008` | False Identity `calculateRefundPreview` | `src/billing.ts:40` | **Fix now** — cheap rename/extract; misleading \"preview\" name is actively dangerous because callers will treat it as pure. |\n| 3 | `crime_00011` | Logic in the Alibi (owner/refund rule) | `src/billing.ts:39` | **Fix now** — encode the comment as a named guard + test alongside #2; same edit window. |\n| 4 | `crime_00004` | Temporal Recklessness (7×) | `src/billing.ts` | **Fix now** — inject a clock; prerequisite for testing #1 and #3 properly. |\n| 5 | `crime_00006` | Test That Proves Nothing | `src/billing.test.ts:4–6` | **Fix now** — 2-minute fix (add an expect or delete). Leaving it gives agents false coverage signal. |\n| 6 | `crime_00002` | Missing Agent Context | repo root | **Fix now** — `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` is ~10 min and prevents repeated bad edits across every later task. |\n| 7 | `crime_00010` | God File `billing.ts` (310 LOC) | `src/billing.ts` | **Defer** — falls out naturally once #1 is extracted; doing both in one PR is fine but don't treat it as separate work. |\n| 8 | `crime_00005` | Temporal Recklessness (5×) | `src/date.ts` | **Defer** — same fix shape as #4, lower leverage. Wait until the clock abstraction exists, then sweep. |\n\n## Duplication (2)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 9 | `crime_00007` | String Sprinkles — `\"enterprise\"` in 4 files | **Fix now** — centralise to an enum/const before someone adds a 5th copy. Cheap and prevents a future round of policy-drift findings. |\n| 10 | `crime_00009` | Concept Alias Drift — tenant / account / team / workspace across 5 files | **Defer** — needs a product call on the canonical term first. Don't mass-rename until that decision exists, otherwise you'll re-do it. |\n\n## Git-history / IA / frontend\n\n**Empty in the top 10.** Worth flagging:\n\n- **Git-history:** every finding has `churn: 0` — the fixture either has no git history or the detector hasn't run with `--changed`. Re-run after a few commits land to surface hotspot-style findings.\n- **IA (runner-ups):** `crime_00012` (duplicated nav source for `/settings/billing`) → **fix now** if you widen the window; `crime_00014` (route metadata drift on the same destination) → **defer**, it resolves as a side-effect of fixing #12.\n- **Frontend:** no dedicated findings; the three `orphaned_destination` rows (`crime_00021–23`) are the closest, all **defer-or-ignore** until someone owns the routes.\n\n## Suggested execution order\n\n`#1 → #2+#3 → #4 → #5 → #6 → #9` as one or two PRs touching `billing.ts`; then `#7` (file split falls out); then a separate session for `#8`, `#10` once product weighs in. Skip nothing — every \"defer\" above has a concrete trigger that surfaces it again.",
