decision, not a mechanical fix; document the canonical term first |\n\n## Empty categories\n\n- **git-history** — no churn signal in this fixture (all `churn = 0`), so no hotspots surfaced. Re-run on a repo with real git history before treating this as \"clean\".\n- **frontend** — the nav / route IA findings (`crime_00012` Duplicated Navigation Source, `crime_00014` Route Metadata Drift) sit at #11–#13 and are the next wave once billing is tamed.\n\n## Suggested execution order\n\n1. **Wave A — billing.ts cleanup (single PR):** #1 → drag #2, #3, #4, #5, #7 along; #10 falls out for free.\n2. **Wave B — clock module:** #6 (`date.ts`) reuses the abstraction introduced in Wave A.\n3. **Wave C — consistency:** #8 (`\"enterprise\"` → constant).\n4. **Wave D — agent on-ramp:** #9 (AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md).\n5. **Deferred:** #10 concept-alias drift — schedule once Wave A lands and you can pick a canonical term without churning a refactor in flight.\n\nNothing in the top 10 warrants **ignore** — every finding is either fixable now or a deliberate defer with a trigger condition.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## What `src/billing.ts` does\n\nA 310-line module that owns invoice + refund logic for plans (including the `\"enterprise\"` tier). Two anchor functions:\n\n- **`calculateRefundPreview`** (lines 40–44) — name suggests a pure calculation, but the body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. The preview is actually a side-effecting operation.\n- **`generateInvoice`** (lines 50–253) — a 204-line \"god function\" that mixes responsibilities and reads wall-clock time at multiple points (lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273).\n\nA comment at line 39 encodes a policy that doesn't appear to live in code: *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\"* That rule is load-bearing but invisible to the type system.\n\n## Files to also read before editing\n\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** — the existing coverage is thin: one test has zero assertions (\"renders the enterprise plan\", lines 4–6) and another uses only weak matchers (\"creates an invoice\", lines 8–10). Don't trust a green run here.\n- **`src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts`** — the literal `\"enterprise\"` is scattered across all four files. Any change to enterprise behaviour likely needs to touch (or at least audit) these.\n- **`src/date.ts`** — already exists and also reads the clock directly; if you introduce a clock abstraction, this is the sibling to align with.\n- **`docs/billing.md`** — part of a tenant/account/organisation/team/workspace alias drift cluster; worth a glance to see which vocabulary the docs use.\n\n## Risks the scan flagged on this file\n\n| Charge | Severity | Why it matters for an edit |\n|---|---|---|\n| God Function (`generateInvoice`, 204 lines) | high | Editing one branch easily misses interactions in another |\n| Temporal Recklessness (7× direct `Date` calls) | medium | Domain code is non-deterministic; tests can't pin time |\n| False Identity (`calculateRefundPreview`) | medium | Callers may treat it as pure — it isn't |\n| God File (310 lines, 5 top-level fns) | medium | Hidden local coupling outside the agent's loaded window |\n| Logic in the Alibi (line 39 comment) | medium | A real policy lives in prose, not code |\n| Unfinished Business (4 TODO/FIXME, lines 183–308) | low | Hard to tell which logic is load-bearing |\n\nCross-cutting risks that touch billing.ts indirectly: the `\"enterprise\"` string-sprinkle (crime_00007) and the route-metadata drift between `/settings/billing` labels in `src/nav/registry.ts` (\"Plans\") vs `src/nav/sidebar.ts` (\"Billing\") vs the page title (\"Subscription\") — relevant if your edit changes how the billing surface is named or navigated.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "**Break: `src/domain/billing.ts` → `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`**\n\nThe cycle is `billing-flow.ts → billing.ts → invoice-view.ts → billing-flow.ts`. That `domain → presentation` edge is the one to remove, for three reasons:\n\n1. **It's the only edge that's also wrong on its own merits.** Finding #2 flags it as a layer violation (`domain cannotImport presentation`). The other two edges in the ring (`application → domain`, `presentation → application`) are directionally sane — application orchestrating domain, presentation rendering application flows. Removing the inverted edge fixes both crimes at once.\n\n2. **Domain should not know about views.** Whatever `billing.ts` is reaching into `invoice-view.ts` for is almost certainly a type, a formatter, or a helper that belongs in the domain layer (or in a shared module both can import). Move it down, not sideways.\n\n3. **Lowest blast radius for the fix.** The presentation→application and application→domain edges are doing real work (UI calling a flow, flow calling domain logic). Inverting either of those would require more restructuring than just relocating whatever the domain is borrowing from the view.\n\n**Concrete next step:** open `src/domain/billing.ts`, find the `import ... from '../presentation/invoice-view'`, and either (a) move the imported symbol into `src/domain/` (if it's a type/value that belongs there), or (b) if it's genuinely view-shaped, invert the dependency — have `invoice-view.ts` accept it as a parameter from the caller in `application/`. If the import is type-only, converting to `import type` also kills the runtime edge, but the layer violation stays — fix the structure, don't paper over it.",
