/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Triage plan — top 10 by agent_risk\n\nRanked by `agent_risk` (per `CLAUDE.md`: aggregate risk drives the default, not severity alone). Note: `verdict` output wasn't included, only `scan` — but `summary.total=22`, `high=1`, so verdict would almost certainly be \"fail\" / non-clean. Also worth noting up front: **every `churn` score is 0**, so there are no git-history findings in this fixture — that category is empty.\n\n## By category\n\n### Structural / testability (5)\n| # | id | charge | risk | action | rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | crime_00001 | God Function (`generateInvoice`, 204 lines) | 0.63 | **fix now** | Only `high`. Anchors most other billing.ts findings (#4, #8, #10, #11, #20) — splitting it makes the rest cheaper. |\n| 3 | crime_00005 | Temporal Recklessness (`src/date.ts`) | 0.61 | **fix now** | This is literally the clock module — define the `now()` injection here first; #9 then consumes it. |\n| 9 | crime_00004 | Temporal Recklessness (`billing.ts`, 7 sites) | 0.53 | **defer** | Blocked on #3 landing. Do as part of the God Function split so call-sites are touched once. |\n| 10 | crime_00008 | False Identity (`calculateRefundPreview`) | 0.52 | **fix now** | Cheap rename / extract; misleading purity is exactly the agent-risk wedge. |\n| 7 | crime_00013 | Unfinished Business (`todo.ts`, 14 markers / 32 LOC) | 0.57 | **defer** | Not a code fix — convert to tracked issues. Low-risk to leave during structural work. |\n\n### IA / agent context (2)\n| # | id | charge | risk | action | rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 2 | crime_00002 | Missing Agent Context | 0.61 | **fix now** | Cheapest item with the largest leverage — write `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` once, every later fix lands safer. Do first. |\n| 5 | crime_00009 | Concept Alias Drift (tenant ↔ account/team/workspace/org) | 0.58 | **defer** | Needs a product decision on the canonical noun — don't rename until #6/#8 land and the product owner picks the term. Pairs with #4 (duplication). |\n\n### Frontend / IA-of-the-app (2)\n| # | id | charge | risk | action | rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 6 | crime_00012 | Duplicated Navigation Source | 0.57 | **fix now** | Pair with #8 — same destination, same fix (single source of truth for `/settings/billing`). |\n| 8 | crime_00014 | Route Metadata Drift (`/settings/billing`) | 0.56 | **fix now** | Same root cause as #6. Do in one PR. |\n\n### Duplication (1)\n| # | id | charge | risk | action | rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 4 | crime_00007 | String Sprinkles (`\"enterprise\"` × 4 files) | 0.60 | **defer** | Resolve alongside #5 (alias drift) — both need the same naming/policy decision. Centralizing the literal before the concept is named just relocates the problem. |\n\n### Git-history\nNone in top 10 (all churn=0 in fixture — no commit history to mine).\n\n## Recommended execution order\n\n1. **crime_00002** (Missing Agent Context) — 30-min unblocker\n2. **crime_00012 + crime_00014** (nav + route metadata) — single PR, narrow blast radius\n3. **crime_00008** (False Identity rename) — cheap, isolated\n4. **crime_00005** (clock in `date.ts`) — define the abstraction\n5. **crime_00001** (God Function split) — biggest structural move; do #9 (#crime_00004) as part of it\n6. *Defer:* crime_00007 + crime_00009 (await canonical-term decision), crime_00013 (issue-tracker bulk move)\n7. *Ignore* — none. Nothing in the top 10 is a false positive worth suppressing; the only suppressed finding is already counted in `suppressed_count: 1`.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Review verdict: review-01-messy-ts-app\n\n22 findings on what's effectively a greenfield diff. Treating the PR as a whole I'd **request changes** — but per-finding triage below.\n\n## Block merge (1)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk | Why block |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00001` | God Function `generateInvoice` (204 lines, 3.4× threshold) | **high / 0.63** | Only `high` severity in the report and it's in a domain function. A 200-line invoice generator landing in a single PR is the kind of artefact that's far cheaper to split before it ships than after callers wire up to its current shape. |\n\n## Warn — fix before merge or file a follow-up (12)\n\nThese cluster around three real problems, not 12 unrelated nits, which is why I'd block the *PR* even though I wouldn't block any of them individually.\n\n**Cluster A — the \"enterprise refund\" rule is structurally unsafe**\n- `crime_00011` Logic in the Alibi (sev 0.5 / ar 0.5) — owner/billing-support rule lives only in a comment at `src/billing.ts:39`.\n- `crime_00008` False Identity `calculateRefundPreview` (sev 0.55 / ar 0.52) — \"preview\" name, but calls `saveRefundAudit` + `sendRefundEmail`. An agent that trusts the name will double-fire side effects.\n- `crime_00007` String Sprinkles `\"enterprise\"` (sev 0.5 / ar 0.6) — same literal spread across api/billing/jobs/ui; same rule will be re-implemented inconsistently next time.\n\n  Together these are a correctness footgun, not three style nits.\n\n**Cluster B — tenant/destination identity is incoherent**\n- `crime_00009` Concept Alias Drift `tenant` (sev 0.55 / ar 0.58) — account/organisation/team/workspace all coexist.\n- `crime_00012` Duplicated Navigation Source `/settings/billing` (sev 0.6 / ar 0.57) — labelled \"Plans\" vs \"Billing\" in two registries.\n- `crime_00014` Route Metadata Drift `/settings/billing` (sev 0.6 / ar 0.56) — four different names across path, file, component, `<title>`, and nav.\n\n  Pick canonical terms before merging or the next PR doubles the inconsistency.\n\n**Cluster C — determinism + agent legibility**\n- `crime_00004` Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` (sev 0.6 / ar 0.53) — 7 raw clock reads in domain code.\n- `crime_00005` Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (sev 0.6 / ar 0.61) — 5 more; date utilities should be the *fix*, not another offender. Higher agent_risk because `test_gap = 1`.\n- `crime_00002` Missing Agent Context (sev 0.6 / ar 0.61) — no AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md/SKILL.md. Cheap to fix; high agent_risk because every future agent edit pays this tax.\n- `crime_00010` God File `src/billing.ts` 310 lines (sev 0.6 / ar 0.5) — only 1.0× threshold, so warn rather than block, but closely linked to crime_00001 — the split will likely resolve both.\n- `crime_00006` Test That Proves Nothing — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has zero asserts (sev 0.45 / ar 0.46). Delete or assert.\n- `crime_00013` Unfinished Business `src/todo.ts` — 14 markers in 32 LOC (sev 0.4 / ar 0.57). The file is mostly TODO noise; triage or drop before merging.\n\n## Ignore — non-blocking, file an issue if you want (9)\n\nAll low severity, agent_risk ≤ 0.51, no evidence of correctness risk.\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / ar | Comment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00015` | Docs-Code Drift `docs/teams.md → ./setup.md` | 0.35 / 0.51 | Stale link; fix opportunistically. |\n| `crime_00016` | Weak Test (weak matcher in `\"creates an invoice\"`) | 0.25 / 0.34 | Tighten when touched. |\n| `crime_00017` | Option Bag Junk Drawer `describeCheckout` | 0.30 / 0.48 | Stylistic; fixture-specific. |\n| `crime_00018` | Return Shape Roulette `resolvePaymentResult` | 0.30 / 0.48 | Add a return type next time it's edited. |\n| `crime_00019` | Negative Flag Maze `!disableBilling && !skipRetry` | 0.25 / 0.47 | Rename when touched. |\n| `crime_00020` | Unfinished Business in `src/billing.ts` | 0.20 / 0.40 | 4 markers, just over threshold. |\n| `crime_00021` | Orphaned `/account/subscription` | 0.40 / 0.46 | All three orphans line up with cluster B — same root cause. Resolving the tenant naming will likely promote or delete them. |\n| `crime_00022` | Orphaned `/team` | 0.40 / 0.46 | Same. |\n| `crime_00023` | Orphaned `/workspace/members` | 0.40 / 0.46 | Same. |\n\n## Net call\n\n**Request changes.** Block on `crime_00001` and the three clusters in Warn (especially A — the refund rule). The Ignore bucket can roll into a follow-up; cluster B will collapse most of it anyway.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/refactor-08-architecture.json:7:  "response": "## Proposed changes\n\n**1. `crime_00002` — Layer Violation (domain → presentation)**\n\n`src/domain/billing.ts` imports `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`. Don't redirect this — **invert it**.\n\n- Define the collaboration as an interface owned by `domain` (e.g. `InvoiceRenderer` port in `src/domain/`).\n- Have `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` implement that port.\n- Inject the implementation at the composition root (likely `application/billing-flow.ts` or an entry point).\n- Delete the `import` from `domain/billing.ts → presentation/invoice-view.ts`.\n\nThis also collapses `crime_00001`: the cycle `billing-flow → billing → invoice-view → billing-flow` exists *only* because of the inverted edge. Remove it and the ring breaks without touching the other two files.\n\n**2. `crime_00003` — Deep Import Abuse**\n\n`src/application/billing-flow.ts` reaches into `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`.\n\n- Change the specifier to `some-pkg` (or whatever subpath the package actually publishes via its `exports` map).\n- If the helper isn't re-exported, that's an upstream gap — file an issue, don't paper over it with a deep path. As a stopgap, wrap the call in a single adapter module in `infrastructure/` so the blast radius of an upstream rename is one file, not many.\n\n## Why their agent risk differs\n\nBoth are \"imports in the wrong place,\" but they fail in different directions:\n\n- **`layer_violation` (agent_risk 0.63)** lies about *where logic lives*. An agent reading `domain/billing.ts` will assume domain is the stable inner ring and edit it without checking presentation; but a presentation change can now reach back through this edge and break domain invariants. The risk is **structural confusion at edit time** — the directory layout no longer predicts the dependency graph, so an agent's mental model is wrong before it writes a single character.\n- **`deep_import` (agent_risk 0.52)** lies about *what's part of the contract*. The path resolves and the code runs, so nothing tells an agent it's holding a package by its private parts. The failure is **deferred to upgrade time** — silent until the vendor reorganises `dist/internal/`, then loud and remote from the edit that introduced it. Lower agent risk because it doesn't mislead reasoning *now*; it just leaves a tripwire for later.\n\nShort version: layer violations corrupt the map an agent reads; deep imports corrupt the assumption that \"if it imports cleanly, it's a supported API.\"",
