/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/review-02-react-dashboard.json:7:  "response": "# Review categorisation — `02-react-dashboard`\n\n**Top-of-file context that drives most calls below:** the fixture mixes pedagogical \"parallel\" folders (`basics/*-starter` ↔ `basics/*-final`, `dashboard/starter-example` ↔ `dashboard/final-example`, `seo/` ↔ `seo/demo/`). A huge chunk of the 104 findings is the duplication detector correctly seeing that these folders are *meant* to be near-clones of each other. That collapses verdicts hard.\n\nNothing here rates **BLOCK** — max severity is `medium`, max `agent_risk` is `0.62`. Block is reserved for high-severity or high-agent-risk findings; these are all petty.\n\n---\n\n## `exact_duplicate_block` — 77 findings (crime_00001–crime_00077)\n\n`severity 0.55 / agent_risk 0.62` across the board.\n\n**Verdict: IGNORE (en masse), with one carve-out.**\n\n- **Why:** every cluster is bounded by the starter↔final / demo pairings. `Layout` in 5 files? Those are 5 sibling tutorial apps. `fetchRevenue` in `dashboard/final-example/app/lib/data.ts` ↔ `dashboard/starter-example/app/lib/data.ts`? Same thing — the *point* of the starter is that the user fills it in until it matches the final. Extracting a shared helper would defeat the pedagogical structure.\n- **agent_risk 0.62 is inflated by `test_gap: 1` and `confidence: 0.95`** — the detector is right about the mechanic, wrong about the consequence here. A reviewer who knew the repo's intent would suppress this whole rule for these paths via `.crimes/` config.\n- **Carve-out — WARN:** `crime_00054` (form-helper subtree duplicated *within* `final-example` between `create-form.tsx` and `edit-form.tsx`, **and again** within `starter-example`). That's not starter↔final parallelism — that's real intra-app duplication of an invoice-form input cluster. Worth a shared component.\n\n---\n\n## `commented_out_code` — 10 findings (crime_00078–81, 89–92, 95–96)\n\nTwo tiers — medium (`severity 0.45`, `agent_risk 0.61`) and low (`severity 0.25`, `agent_risk 0.49–0.51`).\n\n**Verdict: WARN on the medium-severity ones; IGNORE the lows.**\n\n- **WARN (medium):** `crime_00078` (`app/query/route.ts` — 5 lines incl. try/catch/await/return), `crime_00079` (`latest-invoices.tsx` — 38 lines of disabled JSX), `crime_00080` (`revenue-chart.tsx` — 30 lines), `crime_00081` (`pagination.tsx` — 34 lines). These are exactly the agent trap the detector targets: a future agent extending these files will read the dead block as \"the real implementation\" and revive it. Big blocks of commented JSX in a starter are especially dangerous because the starter is *meant* to be edited by agents/learners. Delete them or replace with a one-line \"TODO: implement X\" pointer.\n- **IGNORE (low):** the 2–8 line `console.log` / single-`if` snippets in `data.ts`, `cards.tsx`, `query/route.ts`. Cheap to leave, low confusion potential — `agent_risk ≤ 0.51` reflects that.\n\n---\n\n## `magic_domain_literal_scatter` — 1 finding (crime_00082)\n\n`severity 0.5 / agent_risk 0.6`. Literal `\"status\"` in 5 production files (form fields + actions).\n\n**Verdict: WARN.**\n\nThis is the canonical evidence for an invoice-status policy that has no central definition. Combined with the policy-check finding below, this is the strongest signal in the report. Don't block (it's a known idiomatic Next.js form-field name pattern), but the reviewer should ask: \"Where is the canonical InvoiceStatus enum / zod schema?\" If the answer is \"scattered across five files,\" that's a `.crimes` finding that earns its keep.\n\n---\n\n## `duplicate_component_shape` — 1 finding (crime_00083)\n\n`severity 0.55 / agent_risk 0.57`. Same `<div>` subtree in create-form + edit-form, in both starter and final.\n\n**Verdict: WARN.**\n\nSame logic as the `crime_00054` carve-out — the intra-app duplication (final→final, starter→starter) is the real signal. Reviewer should ask for a shared form-row component before this gets copied a third time.\n\n---\n\n## `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` — 2 findings (crime_00084, crime_00085)\n\n`severity 0.55 / agent_risk 0.57` each. `\"pending\"` and `\"paid\"` compared in 4 files using 2 expression shapes (`invoice.status === \"x\"` vs `status === \"x\"`).\n\n**Verdict: WARN (the most action-worthy in the report).**\n\nThe detector caught what it was designed to catch: status policy that is *already* drifting (two expression shapes). The pairing of `status.tsx` (display) and `edit-form.tsx` (validation) is the classic split-brain that lets paid invoices render as pending after a future refactor. `agent_risk 0.57` is honest — not catastrophic, but cumulative with `crime_00082`. Recommend the PR adds an `isPending(invoice)` / `isPaid(invoice)` policy module and migrates both files before merge. Not a hard block — the existing behaviour works — but the cheapest fix in the report.\n\n---\n\n## `direct_date` — 3 findings (crime_00086–88)\n\n`severity 0.35 / agent_risk 0.51`.\n\n**Verdict: WARN on `actions.ts`, IGNORE on `utils.ts` (×2).**\n\n- **WARN — `crime_00086` (`app/lib/actions.ts:57`):** `new Date()` inside a server action that writes invoice records. This is exactly the testability hazard the detector targets — the timestamp on a created invoice will be wall-time-dependent and untestable without monkey-patching. Inject a clock.\n- **IGNORE — `crime_00087`, `crime_00088` (`app/lib/utils.ts:14`):** the `new Date()` is inside `formatDateToLocal(dateStr)`, which by definition takes a date string and reformats it. The detector saw `new Date(` and flagged it, but it's `new Date(dateStr)` — a parser, not a clock read. False positive worth suppressing in config.\n\n---\n\n## `deep_import` — 2 findings (crime_00093, crime_00094)\n\n`severity 0.35 / agent_risk 0.5`. Both: `react-syntax-highlighter/dist/cjs/styles/prism` in `seo/components/CodeSampleModal.js` and its demo copy.\n\n**Verdict: WARN.**\n\nThis is a real, well-known footgun with `react-syntax-highlighter` — the `dist/cjs/...` path is not its published surface, and it has broken across versions before. Low severity but worth a \"consider switching to the package's documented import\" comment on the PR. Don't block — the package's docs themselves nudge people toward this path for bundle-size reasons, so it's defensible.\n\n---\n\n## `design_token_escape` — 8 findings (crime_00097–104)\n\n`severity 0.4 / agent_risk 0.48`. Hard-coded `px` values in invoice forms, login form, skeletons — all in both `starter` and `final`.\n\n**Verdict: IGNORE.**\n\n- `agent_risk 0.48` is the lowest in the report — the detector itself is uncertain (`confidence 0.75`).\n- These are all Tailwind-using files where the raw px values are inside inline `style={{...}}` for things like input placeholder spacing — i.e., the cases where Tailwind doesn't cleanly cover the use. Suppressible.\n- Even if real, this is exactly the \"petty / single-file\" category the PRD calls out as *not* worth blocking on. The reviewer can leave a non-blocking comment.\n\n---\n\n# Summary table\n\n| Detector | Count | Verdict | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `exact_duplicate_block` | 77 | **IGNORE** (1 carve-out → WARN) | Starter/final parallel folders by design |\n| `commented_out_code` | 10 | **WARN** medium, **IGNORE** low | Big disabled JSX blocks are agent traps |\n| `magic_domain_literal_scatter` | 1 | **WARN** | Invoice status has no canonical definition |\n| `duplicate_component_shape` | 1 | **WARN** | Real intra-app duplication, not pedagogical |\n| `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` | 2 | **WARN** | Already drifting (two expression shapes) |\n| `direct_date` | 3 | **WARN** ×1, **IGNORE** ×2 | Only `actions.ts` reads the clock; `utils.ts` parses |\n| `deep_import` | 2 | **WARN** | Known footgun with this specific package |\n| `design_token_escape` | 8 | **IGNORE** | Lowest agent_risk; petty by PRD definition |\n\n**Net for the reviewer:** zero blocks, ~5 actionable warns (the two status-policy findings, the dead-JSX blocks, the `actions.ts` clock read, the deep import, the intra-app form duplication). Everything else is signal-to-config — the report would look very different with `.crimes/ignore` patterns scoped to the tutorial layout.",
