rt fixed-time behavior in `src/billing.test.ts`.\\n\\n3. Separate refund calculation from refund side effects, and encode the prose rule.\\n   `crime_00004` says `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure but calls side-effect-like functions: `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. `crime_00006` also flags the nearby comment, “Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves,” as logic that is not obviously encoded. I’d make this explicit with a guard like `canRefundEnterprisePlan(...)`, keep a pure `calculateRefundPreview(...)`, and move audit/email into a clearly named command such as `createRefundPreviewAndNotify(...)`. That reduces both naming risk and hidden policy risk.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":51551,\"cached_input_tokens\":36608,\"output_tokens\":539,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":38}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to reduce risk in `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Break up `generateInvoice` (crime_00001 + crime_00010)\n204 lines spanning L50–253 — 3.4× the domain-function threshold and effectively the reason the whole file is over the 310-line `God File` line (crime_00010). This is the single highest-severity, highest-agent-risk finding in the report (severity 0.9, agent_risk 0.63). Extracting cohesive sections (tax calc, line-item assembly, proration, discount application, persistence) into named helpers does double duty: it kills the `large_function` finding *and* drops the file under the `large_file` threshold without a separate split. It also exposes the responsibilities so the next edit doesn't accidentally collide with code 150 lines away.\n\n## 2. Inject a clock and route all time through it (crime_00004)\n7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls scattered across L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Every one of those is a hidden coupling to wall time — and `src/billing.test.ts` already has weak tests (crime_00006 is zero-assertion, crime_00016 uses weak matchers), so there's no safety net catching temporal bugs today. Threading a `Clock`/`now()` dependency through `generateInvoice` (which #1 makes much easier) means proration windows, due-date math, and audit timestamps can finally be tested with fixed instants instead of monkey-patching `Date`. Pairs naturally with the same fix in `src/date.ts` (crime_00005).\n\n## 3. Encode the refund authorisation rule and rename `calculateRefundPreview` (crime_00008 + crime_00011)\nThese two findings are about the same code path and reinforce each other:\n- L39 carries the rule **\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"** as a comment — prose policy that nearby code doesn't obviously encode (crime_00011). An agent extending refunds will not see it.\n- L40–44 `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` (crime_00008). Anyone — human or agent — treating it as a pure preview will trigger emails and audit rows.\n\nFix together: extract the pure calculation as `calculateRefundPreview`, move side effects into a separately-named `commitRefund` (or similar), and encode the owner/enterprise/billing-support rule as a typed guard (e.g. `assertCanRefund(actor, plan)`) so the policy lives in code the type-checker and tests can see. Comment stays only to explain *why*, not *what*.\n\n---\n\nWhy this trio over the rest: the remaining billing.ts findings (`String Sprinkles` for `\"enterprise\"`, 4 TODOs, the file-size flag) are either downstream of #1/#3 or low-leverage cleanup. These three changes together collapse the `God Function`, the `God File`, the temporal coupling, the misleading API, and the hidden authorisation rule — i.e. they retire the high-severity finding and four of the five highest-agent-risk findings touching this file.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3906-586f-7150-97d4-f1c48491f442\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The most likely cause is `crime_00004`: `src/billing.ts` reads wall-clock time directly with `Date.now()` and `new Date()` across billing logic, including several calls inside or near `generateInvoice`.\\n\\nFor a date-boundary failure, that is the strongest signal because the function can observe different times during one invoice generation. If a test runs around midnight, month end, trial expiry, renewal cutoff, or timezone conversion boundary, two separate `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls may land on opposite sides of the boundary. That makes the invoice depend on when the test happened to execute, not only on its inputs.\\n\\nThe high-risk `generateInvoice` finding makes this worse: the date logic is buried inside a 204-line function, so renewal, proration, due date, discounts, and invoice timestamps may be coupled without being obvious.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // Use `now` everywhere in this invoice calculation.\\n  // Do not call Date.now() or new Date() again inside the function.\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen update the failing billing tests to pass a fixed clock:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-31T23:59:59.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nThe key is to capture one deterministic `now` at the boundary of the operation and thread it through the billing calculations. Avoid scattered `Date.now()` calls, especially if the code compares billing periods, expiry dates, invoice dates, or due dates.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":17792,\"output_tokens\":393,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":20}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/refactor-01-large-file.json:7:  "response": "I have what I need. The `large_file` finding (310 / 300 lines, 5 top-level functions) says \"split along clear responsibility boundaries\" — but the file is only 10 lines over threshold, so the structural reason it's large is one thing: the 204-line `generateInvoice` body. The split has to attack that, not just shuffle the slim functions.\n\nNo in-repo callers import from `src/billing.ts` — only `src/billing.test.ts` (per the context tool's `likely_tests`). That means the safe move is to keep `src/billing.ts` as a barrel that re-exports the public API, so no caller paths change.\n\n## Proposed split\n\nAnchored to the evidence in `crime_00010` (310 LOC, 5 top-level functions) and the co-located findings the context tool pulled in (God Function, False Identity on `calculateRefundPreview`, Logic in Comments at line 39, Temporal Recklessness lines 57–273, duplicated tax logic at 145–154 vs. 257–268, FIXME/HACK/XXX/TODO inside `generateInvoice`).\n\n| New file | What moves (current lines) | Tied to which evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| `src/billing/types.ts` | `User`, `InvoiceLine`, `Invoice` (4–31) | Drops file under the 300-line threshold immediately; zero behavioural change. |\n| `src/billing/tax.ts` | `tax()` (257–268) **plus** the inline tax block (145–154) collapsed into the same function | Removes the duplicated tax rule the comment at L145 flags — the structural reason this section is \"two copies of one rule\". |\n| `src/billing/refund.ts` | `calculateRefundPreview` (40–44) | Lets us rename it (`previewAndAuditRefund` or split pure preview from `audit+email`) per the False Identity finding (`crime_00008`), and encode the prose rule at L39 as a guard — Logic in Comments (`crime_00011`). |\n| `src/billing/upgrade.ts` | `recommendUpgrade` (272–305) | Co-locates the \"days since signup\" policy that's currently duplicated between L92 and L273 — the comment at L91