/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "## Which import to break\n\n**Break `src/domain/billing.ts` → `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`.**\n\n## Why\n\nThe scan shows a 3-file cycle and a separate layer violation, but they're the same defect viewed two ways:\n\n- `crime_00002` calls out exactly this edge: domain importing presentation, against the `domain cannotImport presentation` rule.\n- That same edge is one of the three legs of the cycle in `crime_00001`.\n\nSo one cut closes both findings. The other two legs of the ring (application → domain, presentation → application/domain) point in directions a layered architecture expects; removing either of those would fix the cycle but leave the inverted dependency in place, which would likely re-grow into another cycle the next time someone follows the existing pattern.\n\n## How to break it\n\nPick whichever fits what `billing.ts` is actually reaching for:\n\n1. **If it needs a type only** — change the import in `billing.ts` to `import type { … } from '../presentation/invoice-view'`. Type-only imports don't create a runtime edge, so the cycle disappears at zero behavioral cost. Cheapest fix.\n2. **If it needs a value (function/class/constant)** — that value is misplaced. Extract the shared piece (likely an invoice-shaped type or formatter contract) into a neutral module under `src/domain/` (or a new `src/shared/`) that both `domain` and `presentation` import from. Presentation keeps depending on domain; domain stops depending on presentation.\n3. **Invert with an interface** — define the collaboration as an interface in `domain`, have `presentation` implement it, and have `application` wire the concrete implementation in. Heavier, but right if the domain genuinely needs to call into a rendering concern.\n\nOption 1 is the right first try; fall back to 2 if the import resolves to a runtime value.\n\n## What not to do\n\nDon't break the `applica