ented soon.\\n- `crime_00010` `large_file`: **medium**, `agent_risk: 0.50`. Real maintainability signal, but mostly secondary to the blocking `generateInvoice` finding in the same file.\\n- `crime_00011` `logic_in_comments`: **medium**, `agent_risk: 0.50`. A prose-only authorization/refund rule deserves a warning because it can be missed during edits.\\n- `crime_00012` `duplicated_navigation_source`: **medium**, `agent_risk: 0.57`. Two labels for the same destination will cause UI drift.\\n- `crime_00013` `todo_density` in `src/todo.ts`: **medium**, `agent_risk: 0.57`. Very noisy unfinished-work signal; warn unless this file is explicitly fixture/demo-only.\\n- `crime_00014` `route_metadata_drift`: **medium**, `agent_risk: 0.56`. Four competing labels for `/settings/billing` should be cleaned up, but it is not a merge blocker by itself.\\n- `crime_00015` `docs_code_drift`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.51`. Low severity, but the agent risk is high enough to warn because stale docs can mislead future edits.\\n- `crime_00017` `option_bag_junk_drawer`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.48`. Warn due to full test gap and implicit API shape.\\n- `crime_00018` `return_shape_roulette`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.48`. Warn because inconsistent return shapes without an explicit type are easy to misuse.\\n- `crime_00019` `negative_flag_maze`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.47`. Minor but worth flagging before extending the condition.\\n- `crime_00021` `orphaned_destination`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.46`.\\n- `crime_00022` `orphaned_destination`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.46`.\\n- `crime_00023` `orphaned_destination`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.46`.\\n\\n**Ignore**\\n\\n- `crime_00016` `weak_test_signal`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.34`. Weak assertion, but low severity and low agent risk. Track only if touching billing tests.\\n- `crime_00020` `todo_density` in `src/billing.ts`: **low**, `agent_risk: 0.40`. This is below the warning threshold I would use here and is already covered by stronger billing-file findings.\\n\\nNet: I would block on 4 findings, warn on 16, and ignore 2. The merge blockers are the high-risk billing function plus medium findings with `agent_risk >= 0.60`; the rest are cleanup warnings unless they sit directly in the changed area of a follow-up PR.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24642,\"cached_input_tokens\":17792,\"output_tokens\":1102,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":49}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause: `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`\n\n`generateInvoice` reads the system clock **7 times** directly (`5× Date.now()`, `2× new Date()`) at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. That's the classic shape of a date-boundary flake:\n\n- Multiple clock reads inside one logical operation mean the value can **straddle a boundary** (midnight, month-end, billing-period rollover) between the first and last read. An invoice computed across that boundary sees inconsistent \"today\" values in different branches of the same function.\n- Tests can't pin a fixed moment without monkey-patching `Date`, so the test is at the mercy of whatever wall time the CI runner happens to have. A test that passes at 14:00 UTC fails at 23:59:59 UTC when one of those 7 reads lands on the next day.\n- `src/date.ts` (`crime_00005`) has 5 more direct clock reads — likely the helpers `billing.ts` is calling, so the non-determinism compounds.\n\nThe 204-line `generateInvoice` (`crime_00001`) makes this worse: with 7 clock reads spread across that body, it's very plausible different branches resolve \"now\" inconsistently.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\n1. **Inject a clock.** Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): number` or `now(): Date`) and thread it through `generateInvoice` and the helpers in `src/date.ts`. Default to a real clock in production; pass a fixed clock in tests.\n2. **Capture \"now\" once per invoice.** Inside `generateInvoice`, read the clock exactly once at the top and reuse that value — no boundary can be crossed mid-function.\n3. **Add a boundary-pinned test.** With the injected clock, write a test that pins `now` to `23:59:59.500` on a billing-period boundary and asserts the invoice's period/dates are stable. That regression test is what the current suite is missing.\n\nSecondary contributors worth noting but not load-bearing for this bug: `crime_00006` (a billing test with zero assertions — explains why this slipped through) and `crime_00016` (the `creates an invoice` test uses only weak matchers, so it likely wouldn't catch a wrong date even when it runs).",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes for `src/billing.ts`\n\n**1. Break up `generateInvoice` (crime_00001 + crime_00010)**\nThe function spans lines 50–253 — 204 lines, 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold — and the file as a whole is 310 lines (just over the God File threshold). These are the same problem at two scales: one bloated function is dragging the whole module past its limit. Extract cohesive sections (line-item assembly, tax/discount math, persistence, notification) into named helpers in sibling files. This is the single highest-leverage move because it simultaneously lowers `agent_risk` on the God Function (0.63, the highest score in the report) and pulls the file back under the 300-line ceiling. Bonus: the 4 in-function TODOs (crime_00020, lines 183–308) become easier to triage once each lives inside a small, named helper.\n\n**2. Fix `calculateRefundPreview` — rename + encode the hidden rule (crime_00008 + crime_00011)**\nThese two findings sit on adjacent lines (39 and 40–44) and describe the same trap. The comment at line 39 says *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* — a real authorization rule that isn't visible in code. Meanwhile the function named `calculateRefundPreview` actually calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`, so the \"preview\" name lies to callers and agents. Split it into a pure `calculateRefundPreview` (no side effects) and an `issueRefund` (audit + email), and lift the owner/billing-support check into a named guard like `assertCanRefund(actor, plan)` that throws or returns a typed result. The comment becomes redundant once the guard exists — delete it.\n\n**3. Inject a clock (crime_00004)**\n7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls scattered across lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Domain code reading the wall clock means the billing tests (already weak — see crime_00006 with zero assertions) can't pin a fixed moment without monkey-patching. Thread a `clock: { now(): number }` through the module — easiest as a defaulted parameter on `generateInvoice` after the extraction in step 1 — and replace every direct call. This is what unblocks writing the real assertions the test file is missing today.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# PR review: `01-messy-ts-app` baseline introduction\n\n**Headline:** 1 hard block + 2 escalated to block by interaction. Refund flow is the standout — three findings (`crime_00008`, `crime_00011`, plus the time-dependent invoice logic) compose into a single agent footgun that's worse than any of them alone.\n\n**Decision threshold I'm using:**\n- **Block** — high severity, OR mediums whose `agent_risk ≥ 0.5` *and* sit on a correctness-critical path (billing, refunds, money), OR mediums that compose with other findings to mask business rules\n- **Warn** — must address but not before merge; medium severity OR low severity that actively misleads\n- **Ignore** — fix opportunistically; low impact, cosmetic, or already covered by a bigger finding\n\n---\n\n## Block merge (3)\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev / agent_risk | Why it blocks |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00001` | God Function — `generateInvoice` 204 lines | **0.9 / 0.63** | Only `high` in the report. 3.4× threshold inside `billing.ts`. Anything else we add to invoicing lands on top of a function nobody can hold in their head. Refactor before further billing work, not after. |\n| `crime_00008` | False Identity — `calculateRefundPreview` sends email + writes audit | 0.55 / 0.52 | Sub-block scores in isolation, but a name that promises \"preview\" while issuing refund-side-effects is exactly the agent-risk failure mode `crimes` is built for. An agent told \"just compute the preview\" will fire emails. Block on the *kind* of risk, not just the number. |\n| `crime_00011` | Logic in the Alibi — refund authorisation rule lives in a comment | 0.5 / 0.5 | \"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\" — that's a regulated business rule sitting in prose four lines above the function flagged in `crime_00008`. Comment-rule + misleading-name + temporal coupling (`crime_00004`) at the same file is a refund flow nobody should merge as-is. |\n\nThe three above are tightly coupled (all in `src/billing.ts` lines 39–57). I'd ask the PR author to address them as one unit.\n\n---\n\n## Warn (12)\n\nMust fix, but not blocking merge. Grouped by theme.\n\n**Agent context & domain literals**\n- `crime_00002` — Missing Agent Context (0.6 / 0.61). Repo ships no `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md`. High `agent_risk` for a structural finding. Warn rather than block because it's repo-wide hygiene, not a defect in this PR's code.\n- `crime_00007` — String Sprinkles `\"enterprise\"` in 4 files / 4 areas (0.5 / 0.6). One more copy and it's de-facto duplicated policy. Centralise before adding another plan tier.\n- `crime_00009` — Concept Alias Drift, tenant/account/org/team/workspace (0.55 / 0.58). Five terms for one concept across docs and routes. Pick one.\n\n**Time-dependent billing (correctness-adjacent)**\n- `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` × 7 calls (0.6 / 0.53). Invoice generation reading wall time means tests can't pin a moment. Should be block-grade in a vacuum, but is partly subsumed by `crime_00001` (any extract pass will inject a clock).\n- `crime_00005` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` × 5 calls (0.6 / 0.61). Central date utility, `test_gap` 1.0. Fix alongside `crime_00004`.\n\n**Navigation / routing drift**\n- `crime_00012` — Duplicated Navigation Source, `/settings/billing` labeled \"Plans\" vs \"Billing\" (0.6 / 0.57).\n- `crime_00014` — Route Metadata Drift, `/settings/billing` labeled four different ways across path/file/component/title/nav (0.6 / 0.56). Picks up the same destination as `crime_00012`.\n- `crime_00021/22/23` — three Orphaned Destinations: `/account/subscription`, `/team`, `/workspace/members` (0.4 / 0.46 each). Three abandoned routes in one PR is a smell worth raising as a single warn — feature was likely half-extracted. Either link them or delete them.\n\n**Structure & process**\n- `crime_00010` — God File `billing.ts` 310 lines (0.6 / 0.5). Partly resolved by addressing `crime_00001`; warn rather than double-block.\n- `crime_00006` — Test That Proves Nothing, \"renders the enterprise plan\" — zero assertions (0.45 / 0.46). Misleading test signal; delete or assert. Pair with `crime_00016`.\n- `crime_00013` — Unfinished Business in `src/todo.ts`, 14 TODO/FIXME at 424/1k LOC (0.4 / 0.57). The density itself is the signal — agents can't tell load-bearing from aspirational.\n\n---\n\n## Ignore (7)\n\nLow impact, fix opportunistically, or already covered by a higher finding.\n\n| ID | Charge | Sev / agent_risk | Reason to ignore |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00015` | Docs-Code Drift, `docs/teams.md → ./setup.md` missing | 0.35 / 0.51 | Single dead link in a doc. Trivial fix. |\n| `crime_00016` | Test That Proves Nothing, \"creates an invoice\" weak matcher | 0.25 / 0.34 | Same category as `crime_00006`; fix as part of that warn. |\n| `crime_00017` | Option Bag Junk Drawer, `describeCheckout` | 0.3 / 0.48 | Petty crime — name the shape when it next changes. |\n| `crime_00018` | Return Shape Roulette, `resolvePaymentResult` 3 shapes | 0.3 / 0.48 | Annoying but contained to `petty.ts`. |\n| `crime_00019` | Negative Flag Maze, `!disableBilling && !skipRetry` | 0.25 / 0.47 | Cosmetic; rename when the condition next grows. |\n| `crime_00020` | Unfinished Business in `billing.ts`, 12.9/1k LOC | 0.2 / 0.4 | Just over threshold. Resolve naturally during `crime_00001` refactor. |\n\n---\n\n## Cross-finding patterns worth flagging on the PR\n\n1. **Refund cluster** (`crime_00001` + `crime_00008` + `crime_00011` + `crime_00004` lines 50–57): four findings in 220 lines, all on the refund/invoice path. Treat as one refactor.\n2. **`/settings/billing` identity crisis** (`crime_00012` + `crime_00014`): same destination, two findings, four labels — fix together.\n3. **Half-finished tenant feature** (`crime_00009` + `crime_00021–23`): three orphan routes (`/account`, `/team`, `/workspace`) plus the five-word concept drift across those exact files suggests a partially abandoned tenancy rename. The PR author should confirm intent before merge.\n\n**Bottom line:** I'd block on the refund cluster (1, 8, 11), accept the warn list as PR comments, and let the ignore list ride.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes for `src/billing.ts`\n\n**1. Break up `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253).**\nThis is the high-severity God Function — 204 lines, 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold (`crime_00001`). It's also the main reason the file as a whole trips God File at 310 lines (`crime_00010`); splitting the function will likely retire both findings. Extract cohesive sections (line-item assembly, tax/discount math, totals, persistence/email side effects) into named helpers so an agent editing one concern can't silently break another it never loaded into context. Expect this to also reduce the surface area where `Date.now()` calls hide.\n\n**2. Fix `calculateRefundPreview` (lines 40–44) and encode the rule on line 39.**\nTwo findings stack on the same 6 lines: False Identity (`crime_00008` — the `calculate*` prefix promises a pure read but the body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`) and Logic in the Alibi (`crime_00011` — the comment *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* describes a rule that isn't encoded in nearby code). Split into a pure `previewRefund(...)` returning the computed shape, plus an explicit `commitRefund(...)` that does the audit + email, and turn the comment into a named guard like `canRefundEnterprise(role, approvals)` covered by a test. The misleading name plus a hidden authorisation rule is exactly the combination that gets an agent to confidently ship a broken refund flow.\n\n**3. Inject a clock to kill the 7 direct `Date` calls (lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273).**\nTemporal Recklessness (`crime_00004`) — five `Date.now()` and two `new Date()` reads scattered through the domain logic. Right now the only test in `billing.test.ts` that touches this file is the assertion-free \"renders the enterprise plan\" (`crime_00006`), so behaviour around dates is effectively unprotected. Take a `clock: () => Date` (or `now: () => number`) parameter on `generateInvoice` and the refund helpers, default it to `() => new Date()` at the CLI/API boundary, and you can pin time in tests without monkey-patching. Do this *after* step 1 so you're injecting into smaller, already-extracted helpers rather than threading a parameter through a 200-line body.\n\nSkipped from the top 3 but worth queuing next: centralising the `\"enterprise\"` literal (`crime_00007`, 4 files) once the refund/invoice rules above have a clear home to live in.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "**Most likely cause: `crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`.**\n\n`generateInvoice` reads wall time 7 separate times (5× `Date.now()`, 2× `new Date()`) at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Across a 204-line function (`crime_00001`, God Function), those calls can straddle a boundary mid-execution — month rollover, DST shift, midnight UTC, year-end. Two reads that the author assumed were \"the same moment\" can land in different periods, producing inconsistent billing windows, prorations, or due dates. That's the classic profile of a test that passes 99% of the time and fails right at the boundary.\n\nThe supporting evidence in the report:\n- `crime_00006` — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has zero assertions, so the suite isn't actually pinning behaviour.\n- `crime_00016` — `\"creates an invoice\"` uses only weak matchers.\n- No clock abstraction exists (the same crime fires again in `src/date.ts`, `crime_00005`).\n\nSo tests are weak *and* the code depends on wall time. Flake is inevitable near boundaries.\n\n**Proposed fix (matches the finding's `inject_clock` action):**\n\n1. Introduce a `Clock` seam — `interface Clock { now(): Date }` — with a default `systemClock` and a `fixedClock(date)` for tests.\n2. Take it as a parameter (or module-level injected default) in `generateInvoice`. Replace every `Date.now()` / `new Date()` with **one** `const now = clock.now()` captured at the top of the function, then derive every period/cutoff from that single value. This kills the \"two reads, two moments\" bug class outright.\n3. Do the same refactor in `src/date.ts` so helpers don't sneak wall-time reads back in.\n4. Add a regression test with `fixedClock(new Date(\"2026-01-31T23:59:59.999Z\"))` (and one at a DST transition for the local-time path, if applicable). These are the boundaries the current suite can't express without monkey-patching.\n\nThe God Function and the missing assertions are real but secondary — they explain *why nobody caught this*, not *what's failing*. Fix the clock first; the extraction in `crime_00001` becomes easier once `now` is a single parameter instead of seven scattered reads.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r3/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Triage plan — top 10 by aggregate risk\n\nRanked by severity then `agent_risk` (the PRD's default ordering, since `agent_risk` is what makes a `crimes` finding worth surfacing over a linter result).\n\n## Structural\n\n| # | ID | Charge | Where | Why it ranks | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | crime_00001 | God Function | `src/billing.ts:50–253` (`generateInvoice`) | Only **high** in the report; 204 lines, agent_risk 0.63. Edits here are the single biggest \"agent misses an interaction\" risk in the repo. | **Fix now** — extract cohesive sections before any further billing change lands. |\n| 3 | crime_00005 | Temporal Recklessness | `src/date.ts:4–22` | 5 direct clock reads in a helper module that everything else imports — `test_gap` 1.0. Cheap to fix and unblocks deterministic tests everywhere. | **Fix now** — inject a `now()` here first; ripples to crime_00004 for free. |\n| 9 | crime_00004 | Temporal Recklessness | `src/billing.ts` (7 occurrences) | Same root cause as 00005 but inside the God Function. Cleanest if done as part of the 00001 extraction. | **Defer** — bundle into the crime_00001 fix, not a separate change. |\n| 10 | crime_00008 | False Identity | `src/billing.ts:40–44` (`calculateRefundPreview`) | \"preview\" name but calls `saveRefundAudit` + `sendRefundEmail`. Agents will treat it as pure and double-fire side effects. | **Fix now** — rename/split before refactoring the surrounding billing code. |\n| — | crime_00013 | Unfinished Business | `src/todo.ts` (14 markers, 424/kLOC) | High density but the file is named `todo.ts` — likely a scratchpad, not load-bearing. | **Defer** — triage in a sweep; not blocking. |\n\n## IA (information architecture)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | Where | Why it ranks | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 2 | crime_00002 | Missing Agent Context | repo root | No `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` / `SKILL.md`; `package.json` declares a `messy` bin agents can't discover. Cheapest highest-leverage fix in the report. | **Fix now** — add `AGENTS.md` first; everything downstream becomes easier for the next agent that touches this. |\n| 5 | crime_00009 | Concept Alias Drift | docs + `src/routes/{account,team,workspace}` | 4 aliases for \"tenant\" across 5 files. Will cause an agent to add a 5th vocabulary instead of extending one. | **Defer** — needs a product decision on canonical term before code moves. |\n\n## Frontend / routing\n\n| # | ID | Charge | Where | Why it ranks | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 6 | crime_00012 | Duplicated Navigation Source | `src/nav/registry.ts` + `src/nav/sidebar.ts` | Same destination `/settings/billing`, two labels (\"Plans\" vs \"Billing\"). Any agent fixing one label leaves the other stale. | **Fix now** — pick one source of truth; small, mechanical. |\n| 8 | crime_00014 | Route Metadata Drift | `src/routes/settings/billing.tsx` | Same destination labelled 4 ways across path/file/component/title/nav. Bundles naturally with crime_00012. | **Fix now** — same PR as 00012; choose canonical name once. |\n\n## Duplication\n\n| # | ID | Charge | Where | Why it ranks | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 4 | crime_00007 | String Sprinkles | `\"enterprise\"` × 4 files (`api`, `billing`, `jobs`, `ui`) | Domain literal scattered across all 4 layers. Adding the 5th copy is how a plan-tier policy bug ships. | **Fix now** — centralise into a plan/tier constant or enum before any plan-tier work. |\n\n## Git-history\n\nNone of the top 10. Every finding has `churn: 0` — the fixture has no git history, so `hotspots` would currently say nothing. Worth noting in the verdict report rather than triaging.\n\n---\n\n## Suggested execution order\n\n1. **crime_00002** (AGENTS.md) — unblocks everything else for agents, ~15 min.\n2. **crime_00007** (`\"enterprise\"` → constant) — prevents new copies during subsequent edits.\n3. **crime_00012 + crime_00014** (nav +