/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/plan-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Triage plan — top 10\n\nOrdered by aggregate risk (agent_risk + severity), then grouped by detector category. No git-history or frontend findings cracked the top 10 (all churn=0 in this fixture; nav/route findings sit at #12–#14).\n\n## Structural (6)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | File | Action | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | crime_00001 | God Function | `src/billing.ts:50-253` `generateInvoice` | **fix now** | 204-line function, highest agent_risk (0.63). Splitting it also collapses #9 (large_file) and de-risks #3 and #10. Do this first. |\n| 3 | crime_00005 | Temporal Recklessness | `src/date.ts:4-22` | **fix now** | This is `date.ts` itself — the file most likely to *become* the clock abstraction. Land a `now()`/clock interface here before touching billing. |\n| 5 | crime_00006 | Test That Proves Nothing | `src/billing.test.ts:4-6` | **fix now** | Zero asserts = false safety net while you refactor #1. Either assert behaviour or delete. ~5 min. |\n| 7 | crime_00008 | False Identity | `src/billing.ts:40-44` `calculateRefundPreview` | **fix now** | Misleading name + side effects — rename or extract the audit/email call. Cheap and unblocks safe edits to billing. |\n| 10 | crime_00011 | Logic in the Alibi | `src/billing.ts:39` | **fix now** | Hidden refund-permission rule in a comment. Encode as a guard before the surrounding code grows another caller. |\n| 4 | crime_00004 | Temporal Recklessness | `src/billing.ts:57-273` (7×) | **defer** | Same fix as #3, just larger surface. Defer until the clock abstraction from #3 exists, then sweep billing. |\n| 9 | crime_00010 | God File | `src/billing.ts` (310 LOC) | **defer** | Borderline (1.0× threshold) and resolves naturally once #1/#7 split out helpers. Re-scan after structural fixes; don't refactor twice. |\n\n## IA (2)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | File | Action | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 2 | crime_00002 | Missing Agent Context | repo root | **fix now** | Cheapest high-leverage fix in the report. A 1-page `AGENTS.md` documenting the `messy` bin and conventions removes a class of confident-wrong edits. Do alongside #1. |\n| 8 | crime_00009 | Concept Alias Drift | `tenant` group across 5 files | **defer** | Needs a product/design call (canonical term: tenant? account? workspace?). Don't rename until a human picks. Track as backlog. |\n\n## Duplication (1)\n\n| # | ID | Charge | File | Action | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 6 | crime_00007 | String Sprinkles | `\"enterprise\"` in 4 files | **fix now** | Domain literal scattered across api/billing/jobs/ui = duplicated policy waiting to drift. Land a `Plan` enum/constant before the next feature touches plans. |\n\n## Git-history (0)\n\nNo churn data in fixture — all findings show `churn: 0`. Nothing to triage from this category.\n\n## Frontend (0 in top 10)\n\nThe interesting frontend findings — `duplicated_navigation_source` (#12), `route_metadata_drift` (#14), three `orphaned_destination`s (#20–22) — all ranked below the top 10. They're worth a **second wave** after structural cleanup, because they're symptoms of the same `enterprise`/tenant vocabulary mess that #6 and #8 surface.\n\n## Suggested execution order\n\n1. **#2** (`AGENTS.md`) — 15 min, unblocks every later edit\n2. **#5** (clock test) and **#6** (`date.ts` abstraction) — paired commits\n3. **#1** (split `generateInvoice`) → naturally resolves #9 and #4\n4. **#7** (`calculateRefundPreview` rename) and **#10** (encode refund rule)\n5. **#6** (`Plan` constant)\n6. Re-scan, then revisit #8 with a human, and tackle the deferred frontend wave.\n\nNothing in the top 10 is **ignore**-grade — every finding has evidence and a cheap suggested action. The two `defer`s (#4, #8, #9) are blocked on upstream work or a design decision, not low confidence.",
