type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_12\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I ran `crimes context src/billing.ts --format json`. Top 3 changes I’d make:\\n\\n1. Extract `generateInvoice` into cohesive helpers  \\n   Finding: `crime_00001` / `large_function`, high severity.  \\n   `generateInvoice` is 204 lines, 3.4x the domain-function threshold. This is the biggest risk reducer because the function likely mixes pricing, discounts, invoice shaping, dates, and side effects. I’d first extract pure sections with names that preserve behavior, then add focused tests around the extracted policy points.\\n\\n2. Inject time instead of calling the system clock directly  \\n   Finding: `crime_00003` / `direct_date`, medium severity.  \\n   `billing.ts` has 7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, and 273. That makes invoice behavior hard to test deterministically. I’d add a small `clock`/`now` parameter or dependency, defaulting to real time, so tests can pin invoice dates and time-based rules.\\n\\n3. Separate refund preview calculation from side effects  \\n   Finding: `crime_00004` / `name_behavior_mismatch`, medium severity.  \\n   `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure, but the context reports side-effect-like calls including `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. I’d split it into a pure refund preview function plus an explicit side-effect wrapper, or rename the current function to disclose that it records/sends. That reduces caller confusion and prevents agents from caching, reordering, or duplicating something they assume is just calculation.\\n\\nI’d treat the file split finding (`crime_00005`) as a follow-on after extracting `generateInvoice`, not the first move. Splitting a 310-line file is useful, but extracting stable boundaries first makes the split safer.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":155939,\"cached_input_tokens\":124160,\"output_tokens\":1191,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":104}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3902-e710-7741-baa8-09bb59ac369e\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `direct_date` in `src/billing.ts`, especially inside the large `generateInvoice` function.\\n\\nThe scan shows 7 wall-clock reads in billing code: `5× Date.now()` and `2× new Date()` on lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`. For a date-boundary failure, that is the strongest signal: invoice generation is observing real time at multiple points, so a test that starts before midnight/month-end/year-end can finish after the boundary and compute inconsistent billing periods, due dates, proration, or timestamps.\\n\\nThe `large_function` finding makes this worse: `generateInvoice` is 204 lines, so date logic is probably mixed with plan rules, discounts, tax, invoice assembly, and side effects. That increases the chance that different parts of the same invoice use different “now” values.\\n\\nProposed fix: capture or inject a single clock value and use it consistently.\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere instead of Date.now() / new Date()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen tests can pin the boundary case:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nIf the public API should not change, use an options object instead:\\n\\n```ts\\ngenerateInvoice(input, { now: new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\") });\\n```\\n\\nThe key fix is not just replacing `Date.now()` with `new Date()` once. It is making invoice generation use one deterministic timestamp for the whole operation, ideally injected by the caller/test.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":438,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":25}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/codex/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3902-e710-7e72-8349-4e3402d68dc4\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Break the `src/domain/billing.ts -> src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` import.\\n\\nWhy:\\n\\n- It is the edge that violates the architecture rule: `domain cannotImport presentation`.\\n- It is also part of the 3-file runtime cycle:\\n  `billing-flow.ts -> billing.ts -> invoice-view.ts -> billing-flow.ts` or equivalent ring.\\n- The domain layer should not know how invoices are rendered. Presentation can depend on domain concepts, but domain depending on presentation inverts the dependency direction and is the most suspicious runtime edge.\\n\\nBest fix: move any shared type/helper used by both `billing.ts` and `invoice-view.ts` into a neutral module, likely something like:\\n\\n```text\\nsrc/domain/billing-types.ts\\n```\\n\\nor\\n\\n```text\\nsrc/application/invoice-contract.ts\\n```\\n\\nThen have both sides import from that shared module. If `billing.ts` only needs a TypeScript type from `invoice-view.ts`, convert it to `import type`, but the cleaner architectural fix is to stop importing presentation from domain entirely.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":19273,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":243,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":29}}\n",
