/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Review verdict: hold for changes\n\nRubric I'm applying:\n- **Block** — sev ≥ 0.7, **or** sev ≥ 0.5 with agent_risk ≥ 0.5 in a safety-critical area (billing/refund logic).\n- **Warn** — sev ≥ 0.4 or agent_risk ≥ 0.5: worth fixing, not a merge blocker on its own.\n- **Ignore** — sev < 0.3 and agent_risk < 0.5: noise on this PR; address opportunistically.\n\n## Block merge (3)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk | Why block |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 00001 | God Function `generateInvoice` (204 LOC) | 0.90 / 0.63 | Only `high` finding. 3.4× the domain-function threshold inside billing. Future agent edits to one branch will silently miss interactions in another — exactly the failure mode `agent_risk` is meant to flag. |\n| 00004 | Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` (7 clock reads) | 0.60 / 0.53 | Wall-clock reads scattered through invoice generation. Tests can't pin time without monkey-patching, and the file has no real assertions to fall back on. In billing this is invoice-correctness risk, not style. |\n| 00008 | False Identity `calculateRefundPreview` | 0.55 / 0.52 | Name says pure preview, body calls `saveRefundAudit` + `sendRefundEmail`. Refund side effects under a \"preview\" verb is the kind of mislabelling that causes double-refunds when an agent calls it speculatively. Promoted to block on domain (refunds + audit trail). |\n\n## Warn — fix before next release, don't block this merge (14)\n\nHigher-impact warnings (sev ≥ 0.5 **or** agent_risk ≥ 0.55):\n\n- **00002** Missing Agent Context (0.60 / 0.61) — repo-level, predates this PR; flag to follow up.\n- **00005** Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (0.60 / 0.61) — utility module, lower blast than 00004 but same fix.\n- **00007** \"enterprise\" literal in 4 files (0.50 / 0.60) — duplicated policy risk; centralise before a 5th copy lands.\n- **00009** Concept Alias Drift (account/organisation/team/workspace) (0.55 / 0.58) — pick canonical term.\n- **00010** God File `billing.ts` 310 LOC (0.60 / 0.50) — only 1.0× threshold; will resolve when 00001 is extracted.\n- **00011** Logic in the Alibi: \"Only owners can refund enterprise plans…\" (0.50 / 0.50) — unencoded refund rule next to 00008. Encode as a guard.\n- **00012** Duplicated Navigation Source `/settings/billing` (0.60 / 0.57) — two labels (Plans vs Billing).\n- **00014** Route Metadata Drift `/settings/billing` (0.60 / 0.56) — 4 names for one destination.\n\nMedium warnings (sev 0.35–0.45):\n\n- **00006** Test with 0 assertions in `src/billing.test.ts` (0.45 / 0.46) — actively misleads; delete or assert. Borderline block given the billing context, but it's a single test.\n- **00013** 14 TODO/FIXME in `src/todo.ts` (0.40 / 0.57) — 424/1k LOC is severe density; triage required even if individual markers are small.\n- **00015** Broken doc link `docs/teams.md → ./setup.md` (0.35 / 0.51) — agents will follow stale instructions.\n- **00021–00023** Orphaned routes `/account/subscription`, `/team`, `/workspace/members` (0.40 / 0.46 each) — three dead destinations cluster with 00009 (alias drift across the same surfaces). Could be in-flight work, but unlinked routes are typically half-finished refactors. Ask the author before merging which are intentional.\n\n## Ignore on this PR (5)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk |\n|---|---|---|\n| 00016 | Weak-matcher test \"creates an invoice\" | 0.25 / 0.34 |\n| 00017 | Option Bag `describeCheckout` | 0.30 / 0.48 |\n| 00018 | Return Shape Roulette `resolvePaymentResult` | 0.30 / 0.48 |\n| 00019 | Negative Flag Maze (`!disableBilling && !skipRetry`) | 0.25 / 0.47 |\n| 00020 | 4 TODOs in `billing.ts` (12.9/1k LOC, barely over threshold) | 0.20 / 0.40 |\n\nAll in `src/petty.ts` or just above noise floor. Worth a cleanup pass, not a review comment.\n\n## Summary\n\n**3 block / 14 warn / 5 ignore.** The blockers cluster in billing: one giant function (00001), wall-clock reads inside it (00004), and a misnamed refund function with side effects (00008). Recommend hold until those three are addressed; the rest can ship as a follow-up tracking issue.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# src/billing.ts — context summary\n\n## What the file does\nA 310-line domain module with 5 top-level functions covering billing logic. Its centerpiece is `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253, 204 lines), and it includes `calculateRefundPreview` (lines 40–44) which despite its name performs side effects (`saveRefundAudit`, `sendRefundEmail`). The file hard-codes the `\"enterprise\"` plan literal, reads wall-clock time in 7 places, and carries a prose-only authorization rule in a comment at line 39: *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\"*\n\n## Files to read before editing\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** — the only test file, and it's weak (one zero-assertion test, one with only weak matchers). Don't trust a green bar here.\n- **`src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts`** — all share the `\"enterprise\"` literal. Any plan-shape change ripples to these.\n- **`src/date.ts`** — also flagged for Temporal Recklessness; likely candidate for / blocker to a shared clock abstraction.\n- **Definitions of `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`** — referenced by `calculateRefundPreview`, needed to understand the hidden side-effect surface.\n- **`src/routes/account/subscription.tsx`** and friends — concept-alias drift around tenant/account/organisation, relevant if the edit touches who-owns-what.\n\n## Risks the scan flagged on this file\n| Severity | Charge | Detail |\n|---|---|---|\n| **high** | God Function | `generateInvoice` is 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold |\n| medium | Temporal Recklessness | 5× `Date.now()` + 2× `new Date()` across lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 |\n| medium | False Identity | `calculateRefundPreview` reads pure but writes (audit + email) |\n| medium | String Sprinkles | `\"enterprise\"` duplicated across 4 production files |\n| medium | God File | 310 lines, just over the 300 threshold |\n| medium | Logic in the Alibi | refund rule lives in a comment, not in code |\n| low | Unfinished Business | 4 TODO/FIXME/HACK/XXX markers (lines 183–308) |\n\n## Practical implication for the edit\nBefore touching `generateInvoice` or refund logic: pin a clock, treat `calculateRefundPreview` as side-effecting, and assume the `\"enterprise\"` literal and the comment-rule at line 39 both need to move (or at minimum be honored) anywhere policy is changed. The tests will not catch regressions — add assertions if you change behavior.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause\n\n**`crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`.** Seven direct reads of `Date.now()` / `new Date()` at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 — all inside the `generateInvoice` God Function (lines 50–253, `crime_00001`). Every call observes wall time at runtime, so any test that exercises billing-period math will flip behaviour at month/year/DST/UTC boundaries depending on *when* the suite runs. `src/date.ts` (`crime_00005`) has the same problem and is presumably what `billing.ts` is calling into, so the rot is on both sides of the boundary.\n\nTwo amplifiers explain why this isn't already caught:\n- `crime_00006` — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has **zero** assertions, so it can't fail no matter what date hits it.\n- `crime_00016` — `\"creates an invoice\"` uses only weak matchers, so it passes on any object-shaped output, masking off-by-one period math.\n\nCombined: real date bugs slip through because the tests don't assert the values that would change at a boundary, and the production code reads the clock seven times in one function so reproducing the failure locally is a coin flip.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\n1. **Inject a clock.** Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): Date`) and thread it through `generateInvoice` (and the helpers in `src/date.ts`). Default to a `systemClock` in production, pass a `fixedClock(new Date('2026-02-28T23:59:59Z'))` in tests. Replace all 7 sites in `billing.ts` and 5 in `date.ts`.\n2. **Pin the failing boundary in a new test** *before* changing the code — e.g. invoice generated at `2026-02-28T23:59:59.500Z` for a monthly plan should still bill February, not March. Use the injected clock so it's deterministic.\n3. **Strengthen `creates an invoice`** to assert the period start/end dates, not just truthiness — otherwise the regression that's flaking today walks back in tomorrow.\n4. **Don't extract `generateInvoice` in the same change.** The God Function (`crime_00001`) is the right next refactor, but doing it concurrently with a clock injection makes the diff unreviewable and risks a different bug. Land the clock fix, then split.\n\nStep 1 is the minimum to make the boundary test deterministic; steps 2–3 are what keep it from regressing. The God Function and the `enterprise` literal scatter (`crime_00007`) are real but unrelated to this bug — separate PRs.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Decompose `generateInvoice` (crime_00001, reinforced by crime_00010)\nThe 204-line `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253) is the highest-severity finding in the whole scan: `severity 0.9`, `agent_risk 0.63`, 3.4× the 60-line domain-function threshold. It's also the dominant reason the file as a whole crossed the 300-line God File threshold (crime_00010). Extract cohesive sections (line-item building, tax/discount, totals, persistence/notify) into named helpers. Doing this once collapses *two* findings and gives every other refactor below a smaller surface to work against — so it goes first.\n\n## 2. Inject a clock (crime_00004)\nSeven direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 make the billing pipeline non-deterministic and force any test to monkey-patch wall time. `test_gap 0.5` and a single weak-assertion test in `billing.test.ts` (crime_00006, crime_00016) say the safety net is already thin — every clock read in domain code makes it harder to add a real one. Thread a `now(): Date` (or `Clock`) through the call sites surfaced in step 1; the extraction makes the injection mechanical instead of invasive.\n\n## 3. Fix the refund seam: rename `calculateRefundPreview` *and* encode the comment rule (crime_00008 + crime_00011)\nThese two findings sit on adjacent lines (39 and 40–44) and describe the same hazard from two angles:\n- `calculateRefundPreview` reads as pure (`agent_risk 0.52`) but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` — an agent will treat it as side-effect-free and call it speculatively.\n- The authorization rule *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* lives in a comment, not in code (`agent_risk 0.5`).\n\nSplit into a pure `previewRefund(...)` and an explicit `executeRefund(...)`, and lift the owner/billing-support check into a named guard (e.g. `assertCanRefund(actor, plan)`) with a test. That converts the most agent-hostile spot in the file — a load-bearing prose rule guarded by a misleadingly-named function — into something a coding agent can actually see.\n\n---\n\nDeferred deliberately: the `\"enterprise\"` literal scatter (crime_00007) and the 4 TODOs (crime_00020) are real but lower-leverage; they're easier to handle once the function is decomposed and the refund seam is honest.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.3/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "## Cycle and the break\n\nThe runtime cycle is:\n\n```\napplication/billing-flow.ts  →  domain/billing.ts  →  presentation/invoice-view.ts  →  application/billing-flow.ts\n```\n\n**Break the `domain → presentation` edge** — remove the `import { renderInvoice }` in `src/domain/billing.ts:2`.\n\n### Why that edge\n\nThree reasons, in priority order:\n\n1. **It's the only edge that's also wrong on its own.** crimes flagged it independently as a `layer_violation` (`domain cannotImport presentation`). The other two edges (`application → domain`, `presentation → application`) are at worst awkward, not architecturally invalid. Cutting this one resolves both findings (`crime_00001` and `crime_00002`) with one change.\n2. **Direction of change.** Domain is supposed to be the stable core; presentation depends on it, not the reverse. `chargeCustomer` calling `renderInvoice` is the inversion — the domain function is producing a rendered string, which is presentation's job.\n3. **Smallest blast radius.** `chargeCustomer` has one call site (`runBillingFlow`). Refactor: domain returns the charge result (e.g. `{ amount }` or just `amount`), and the caller in application — or presentation — formats it. No new shared module needed.\n\n### Minimal fix\n\n```ts\n// src/domain/billing.ts\nexport function chargeCustomer(amount: number): number {\n  return amount; // pure domain — no rendering\n}\n```\n\n```ts\n// src/application/billing-flow.ts — composes domain + presentation\nimport { chargeCustomer } from \"../domain/billing.js\";\nimport { renderInvoice } from \"../presentation/invoice-view.js\";\n\nexport function runBillingFlow(): string {\n  return renderInvoice(chargeCustomer(100));\n}\n```\n\n```ts\n// src/presentation/invoice-view.ts — no longer calls back into application\nexport function renderInvoice(amount: number): string {\n  return `Invoice: ${amount}`;\n}\n```\n\nThat leaves a clean layering: `application → { domain, presentation }`, no cycle, no layer violation. The `deep_import` finding (`crime_00003`) is unrelated and stays — fix separately by using `some-pkg`'s public entry.",
