/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/review-02-react-dashboard.json:7:  "response": "# PR Review Verdict: `02-react-dashboard`\n\n**Top-line:** No findings are `high` severity, and the codebase is clearly a Next.js examples monorepo (`basics/*-starter` vs `basics/*-final`, `dashboard/starter-example` vs `dashboard/final-example`, `seo/` vs `seo/demo/`). Cross-tutorial duplication is the *intent*, not a defect. **Nothing here blocks merge.** A handful of within-app issues are worth flagging.\n\nCounts: 104 total — 85 medium, 19 low, 0 high.\n\n---\n\n## `exact_duplicate_block` — 77 findings (scores: sev 0.55, agent_risk 0.62)\n\n**Verdict: IGNORE (almost all) / WARN (the within-app pairs).**\n\nJustification: every cross-directory pair (`crime_00001`–`crime_00077`) is across tutorial step folders. The `severity 0.55` + `agent_risk 0.62` score is correct *in principle* (an edit has to land in every copy), but the whole point of `basics/dynamic-routes-starter` vs `basics/dynamic-routes-step-1` is that they're snapshots of the same lesson at different stages. Coalescing them defeats the docs. Same for `seo/demo` and `seo/`.\n\n**Within-app duplicates worth a WARN** (same app, not across teaching steps):\n- `crime_00054`, `crime_00055`, `crime_00056`, `crime_00057`: `create-form.tsx` ↔ `edit-form.tsx` *within* `dashboard/final-example` — legitimate near-twin forms. `agent_risk 0.62` is load-bearing here; an agent fixing a bug in one form will likely miss the other. → **WARN**, suggest a shared `<InvoiceForm>`.\n\n**Everything else in this detector class** → **IGNORE** with a `.crimes/ignore` rule scoped to the tutorial subtrees (`basics/**`, `seo/demo/**`, paired `starter-example`/`final-example`). Without that suppression the report drowns the signal.\n\n---\n\n## `commented_out_code` — 10 findings (sev 0.25–0.45, agent_risk 0.49–0.61)\n\n**Verdict: WARN.**\n\nThe medium-severity ones (`crime_00078`–`crime_00081`, agent_risk 0.61) all live in `dashboard/starter-example/` — they are *teaching scaffolds* (a \"fill in this body\" snippet for learners). That same property is what makes them an agent-risk: an LLM extending these files will absolutely revive the disabled snippet. **WARN, don't block** — but the PR author should either delete the corpses or wrap them in `/* TODO(student): ... */` blocks that read as instructional, not as dead code.\n\nThe low-severity ones (`crime_00089`–`crime_00096`, agent_risk 0.49–0.51) are 2–4 line snippets — same reasoning, lower priority. WARN, batch them into a single cleanup commit.\n\n---\n\n## `magic_domain_literal_scatter` — 1 finding (sev 0.50, agent_risk 0.60)\n\n**Verdict: WARN.** `crime_00082`: the literal `\"status\"` scattered across 5 form/action files. Real policy literal, not test-only. Agent risk is real (next edit drifts one site). Recommend an `INVOICE_STATUS_FIELD` constant or a Zod schema field reference — cheap fix.\n\n---\n\n## `duplicate_component_shape` — 1 finding (sev 0.55, agent_risk 0.57)\n\n**Verdict: WARN.** `crime_00083`: same `<div>` subtree across create-form/edit-form in both example trees. Pairs with the duplicate-block findings above; folds into the same \"extract shared `<InvoiceForm>`\" recommendation.\n\n---\n\n## `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` — 2 findings (sev 0.55, agent_risk 0.57)\n\n**Verdict: WARN.** `crime_00084` (`\"pending\"`) and `crime_00085` (`\"paid\"`) are exactly the kind of finding `crimes` is built to catch — status comparisons replicated across forms and the status badge, with **two distinct expression shapes** (`invoice.status === \"pending\"` vs `status === \"pending\"`). That divergence is the agent-risk story: a rule change will land on one shape and miss the other. Recommend `isPending(invoice)` / `isPaid(invoice)` policy helpers. Worth flagging in PR review even though severity is medium.\n\n---\n\n## `direct_date` — 3 findings (sev 0.35, agent_risk 0.51)\n\n**Verdict: IGNORE.**\n- `crime_00086`: `new Date()` in `app/lib/actions.ts:57` — generating an invoice timestamp on insert. Reasonable for this stage; clock injection is overkill here.\n- `crime_00087`/`crime_00088`: inside `formatDateToLocal` in `utils.ts` — a *date formatter* receiving a string and producing a locale string. Not domain logic. False positive in spirit.\n\nSeverity 0.35 + low blast radius reinforce: not worth a comment.\n\n---\n\n## `deep_import` — 2 findings (sev 0.35, agent_risk 0.50)\n\n**Verdict: WARN (informational).** `crime_00093`/`crime_00094`: `react-syntax-highlighter/dist/cjs/styles/prism` is the package's *documented* style import path — annoying but not actually a private-API leak. Low priority, but worth a comment in case a future agent copies this pattern elsewhere where it *would* be unsafe.\n\n---\n\n## `design_token_escape` — 8 findings (sev 0.40, agent_risk 0.48)\n\n**Verdict: IGNORE.** All 8 (`crime_00097`–`crime_00104`) flag hardcoded `px` values in Next.js example forms/login/skeletons. This is example code teaching Tailwind — there is no design-token system in place to escape. Low severity, lowest agent_risk in the report. Suppress for this fixture; the detector itself is fine.\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation to PR author\n\n- Block: **nothing**.\n- Fix in this PR (cheap, high agent-risk-reduction):\n  - Extract `isPending`/`isPaid` policy helpers (`crime_00084`, `crime_00085`).\n  - Extract a shared `<InvoiceForm>` for the within-app create/edit pair (`crime_00054`–`crime_00057`, `crime_00083`).\n  - Centralize the `\"status\"` field literal (`crime_00082`).\n  - Delete commented-out scaffolding in `dashboard/starter-example/` or re-tag as instructional (`crime_00078`–`crime_00081`).\n- Suppress via `.crimes/ignore`: cross-tutorial duplication (`basics/**` step-to-step, `*-starter` ↔ `*-final`, `seo/demo` ↔ `seo/`), and `design_token_escape` for the examples tree.\n- Defer / informational: deep-import findings, `direct_date` findings.\n\nThe signal-to-noise issue here is structural: `crimes` is treating a tutorial monorepo as a single app. The fix is configuration (`.crimes/ignore` scoping), not 77 PR comments.",
