und preview calculation from refund side effects**\\n   Findings: `crime_00004` / `name_behavior_mismatch`, plus `crime_00006` / `logic_in_comments`\\n   `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. There’s also a nearby prose-only rule: “Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.” I’d split this into a pure preview function and an explicit side-effecting workflow, then encode the owner/support rule as a named guard with tests. That makes callers less likely to accidentally send email or bypass refund policy.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":60782,\"cached_input_tokens\":41216,\"output_tokens\":538,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":47}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "Top 3 changes for `src/billing.ts`, ranked by what most reduces agent risk per unit of effort:\n\n**1. Break up `generateInvoice` (crime_00001, severity 0.9 / agent_risk 0.63)**\n204 lines (50–253), 3.4× the 60-line threshold — the only `high` in the report and the single biggest reason an agent will confidently edit one section while breaking another. Extract cohesive sections (line items, tax/discount math, totals, persistence/notification) into named helpers. This change also retires crime_00010 (file is 310 lines, just over the 300 threshold) since splitting `generateInvoice` will naturally pull half the file into smaller modules.\n\n**2. Inject a clock; stop reading wall time inside the function (crime_00004, agent_risk 0.53)**\n7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls scattered across `generateInvoice` (lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273). Combined with crime_00006 (the \"renders the enterprise plan\" test has zero asserts) and crime_00016 (weak matchers in \"creates an invoice\"), nothing currently pins invoice-issued-at or due-date behaviour. Take a `now: () => Date` (or `Clock`) parameter, default it at the CLI boundary, and the function becomes testable without monkey-patching globals — which then lets fix #1's extracted helpers be unit-tested cheaply.\n\n**3. Fix the `calculateRefundPreview` lie and encode the owner-refund rule (crime_00008 + crime_00011, lines 39–44)**\nThese are one cluster, not two. `calculateRefundPreview` (line 40) sounds pure but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` — an agent will treat it as safe to call from anywhere. The comment immediately above (\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\") encodes an authorization rule that doesn't appear to be enforced in nearby code. Split the function into a pure `calculateRefundPreview` (returns the numbers) and an explicit `processRefund` (does the audit + email + auth check), and turn the comment into a named guard like `assertCanRefund({ actor, plan })`. This converts two hidden contracts — \"this name lies\" and \"this rule lives only in prose\" — into things the type system and tests can defend.\n\nCommon thread: each fix shrinks the implicit context an agent has to hold in its head to edit `billing.ts` safely. #1 shrinks the surface, #2 removes a hidden input (wall time), #3 makes two hidden contracts explicit.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3902-e710-7741-baa8-09bb59ac369e\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `direct_date` in `src/billing.ts`, especially inside the large `generateInvoice` function.\\n\\nThe scan shows 7 wall-clock reads in billing code: `5× Date.now()` and `2× new Date()` on lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`. For a date-boundary failure, that is the strongest signal: invoice generation is observing real time at multiple points, so a test that starts before midnight/month-end/year-end can finish after the boundary and compute inconsistent billing periods, due dates, proration, or timestamps.\\n\\nThe `large_function` finding makes this worse: `generateInvoice` is 204 lines, so date logic is probably mixed with plan rules, discounts, tax, invoice assembly, and side effects. That increases the chance that different parts of the same invoice use different “now” values.\\n\\nProposed fix: capture or inject a single clock value and use it consistently.\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: GenerateInvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere instead of Date.now() / new Date()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen tests can pin the boundary case:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nIf the public API should not change, use an options object instead:\\n\\n```ts\\ngenerateInvoice(input, { now: new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\") });\\n```\\n\\nThe key fix is not just replacing `Date.now()` with `new Date()` once. It is making invoice generation use one deterministic timestamp for the whole operation, ideally injected by the caller/test.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24636,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":438,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":25}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.4/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to reduce risk in `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Break up `generateInvoice` (crime_00001 + crime_00010)\n204 lines spanning L50–253 — 3.4× the domain-function threshold and effectively the reason the whole file is over the 310-line `God File` line (crime_00010). This is the single highest-severity, highest-agent-risk finding in the report (severity 0.9, agent_risk 0.63). Extracting cohesive sections (tax calc, line-item assembly, proration, discount application, persistence) into named helpers does double duty: it kills the `large_function` finding *and* drops the file under the `large_file` threshold without a separate split. It also exposes the responsibilities so the next edit doesn't accidentally collide with code 150 lines away.\n\n## 2. Inject a clock and route all time through it (crime_00004)\n7 direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls scattered across L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Every one of those is a hidden coupling to wall time — and `src/billing.test.ts` already has weak tests (crime_00006 is zero-assertion, crime_00016 uses weak matchers), so there's no safety net catching temporal bugs today. Threading a `Clock`/`now()` dependency through `generateInvoice` (which #1 makes much easier) means proration windows, due-date math, and audit timestamps can finally be tested with fixed instants instead of monkey-patching `Date`. Pairs naturally with the same fix in `src/date.ts` (crime_00005).\n\n## 3. Encode the refund authorisation rule and rename `calculateRefundPreview` (crime_00008 + crime_00011)\nThese two findings are about the same code path and reinforce each other:\n- L39 carries the rule **\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"** as a comment — prose policy that nearby code doesn't obviously encode (crime_00011). An agent extending refunds will not see it.\n- L40–44 `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` (crime_00008). Anyone — human or agent — treating it as a pure preview will trigger emails and audit rows.\n\nFix together: extract the pure calculation as `calculateRefundPreview`, move side effects into a separately-named `commitRefund` (or similar), and encode the owner/enterprise/billing-support rule as a typed guard (e.g. `assertCanRefund(actor, plan)`) so the policy lives in code the type-checker and tests can see. Comment stays only to explain *why*, not *what*.\n\n---\n\nWhy this trio over the rest: the remaining billing.ts findings (`String Sprinkles` for `\"enterprise\"`, 4 TODOs, the file-size flag) are either downstream of #1/#3 or low-leverage cleanup. These three changes together collapse the `God Function`, the `God File`, the temporal coupling, the misleading API, and the hidden authorisation rule — i.e. they retire the high-severity finding and four of the five highest-agent-risk findings touching this file.",
