/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "## Cycle\n\n`src/application/billing-flow.ts` → `src/domain/billing.ts` → `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` → `src/application/billing-flow.ts`\n\n## Recommendation: break `domain/billing.ts → presentation/invoice-view.ts`\n\nThat edge is the one to cut, and `crimes` is telling you so with two findings stacked on the same import:\n\n1. **`crime_00002` layer violation** — `domain cannotImport presentation`. Domain is the innermost layer; it must not know about how invoices are rendered. Every other edge in the ring is layer-legal:\n   - `application → domain` ✅ (application orchestrates domain)\n   - `presentation → application` ✅ (UI calls into the flow)\n   - `domain → presentation` ❌ ← inverts the dependency direction\n2. **`crime_00001` circular dependency** — removing any one edge breaks the cycle, but only this edge also fixes an architectural defect. Cutting either of the other two would require inventing a contrived workaround in a layer that was correctly placed.\n\n## How to break it\n\nWhatever `billing.ts` is reaching into `invoice-view.ts` for is almost certainly one of:\n\n- **A type** (e.g. `InvoiceViewModel`) — convert to `import type { … } from '../presentation/invoice-view'`. Type-only imports are erased at compile time and contribute **zero** runtime edges, so the cycle disappears without moving code. Cheapest fix.\n- **A shared value/helper** (formatter, constant, shape) — extract it into a neutral module (e.g. `src/domain/invoice-types.ts` or `src/shared/`) that both `domain` and `presentation` import from. `presentation` keeps depending on `domain`; `domain` no longer reaches sideways.\n- **A function `domain` calls on the rendered view** — that's a true inversion; introduce an interface owned by `domain` (e.g. `InvoicePresenter`) and have `presentation` implement it. `domain` depends on its own port, not on the adapter.\n\nIn priority order: try the `import type` conversion first (one-line fix, no architectural change), then extraction, then dependency-inversion via an interface.\n\n## Why not break one of the other two edges\n\n- Cutting `application → domain` would force the billing flow to duplicate domain logic — worse than the cycle.\n- Cutting `presentation → application` would orphan the view from the flow it renders — also worse.\n\nOnly the `domain → presentation` edge is *both* load-bearing-for-the-cycle *and* architecturally wrong. Fix it once, resolve both findings.\n\n## Sidebar: `crime_00003` is unrelated\n\nThe `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js` deep import lives in `billing-flow.ts` and has nothing to do with the cycle — address it separately by switching to the package's public entry point.",
