/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.5/claude/refactor-01-large-file.json:7:  "response": "## Plan: split `src/billing.ts` along its 5 top-level responsibilities\n\n**What the `large_file` finding actually says** (crime_00010 / crime_00005 in context): 310 lines, 1.0× the 300 threshold, **5 top-level functions**. The threshold breach is marginal — but the same scan also reports `generateInvoice` is 204 lines (66% of the file), 7 `Date` reads scattered 57→273, two duplicated business rules (tax + loyalty/age), and a prose-only refund authorization rule at line 39. The split should carve the file along the responsibility seams the evidence already names, not just shave lines.\n\n### Target layout\n\n```\nsrc/billing/\n  types.ts        # User, InvoiceLine, Invoice (lines 4–31)\n  tax.ts          # tax() (257–268)   ← duplicated rule (line 145 block)\n  upgrade.ts      # recommendUpgrade() (272–305)  ← owns the line-273 Date\n  refunds.ts     # calculateRefundPreview() (40–44) + line-39 rule\n  invoices.ts    # generateInvoice() + listRecentInvoices() (50–253, 307–310)\n  index.ts        # re-exports, so the public surface stays `billing`\n```\n\n### Order (each step lowers risk for the next)\n\n1. **`types.ts`** — pure type move. No behaviour, no callers affected. Required first because every other file imports `User` / `Invoice` / `InvoiceLine`.\n2. **`tax.ts`** — 12-line standalone function. After extracting, the duplicated inline block inside `generateInvoice` (lines 145–157, called out by the `// duplicated business rule — also lives in tax()` comment at line 145) becomes a one-line `tax(user.country, afterDiscount)` call. Closes a known duplication that the file evidence flags by name.\n3. **`upgrade.ts`** — `recommendUpgrade` is the only function outside `generateInvoice` that reads the wall clock (line 273, one of the 7 Date sites). Isolating it makes it the obvious first target for the `inject_clock` action on crime_00004 without dragging `generateInvoice` into the same change.\n4. **`refunds.ts`** — `calculateRefundPreview` (5 lines) + the line-39 comment (\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"). The split is the natural moment to act on crime_00008 (False Identity: saveRefundAudit/sendRefundEmail) and crime_00011 (encode the comment as a real guard). Don't bundle those edits into this PR — extract first, refactor in a follow-up.\n5. **`invoices.ts`** — `generateInvoice` (the remaining ~204 lines) plus the 4-line `listRecentInvoices`. After steps 2–4 land, this file is ~210 lines and below threshold. The internal decomposition of `generateInvoice` is the separate concern owned by crime_00001 — explicitly out of scope for the file-level split.\n6. **`index.ts`** — `export * from \"./types\"; export * from \"./invoices\"; ...` so existing import sites don't churn.\n\n### Callers to update\n\nI grepped for `from \".*billing\"` and for each exported symbol across `examples/messy-ts-app`:\n\n- **No external import sites exist in this fixture.** `src/billing.test.ts` defines local stubs (`renderEnterprisePlan`, `createInvoice`) and does not import from `src/billing.ts`.\n- That means the actual update list is: nothing in this repo. If `billing.ts` were imported from elsewhere, the `index.ts` re-export keeps `import { generateInvoice } from \"./billing\"` valid; callers using a deep path would need `./billing/invoices` instead, but none exist here.\n\n### What this does **not** fix (and shouldn't, in one PR)\n\n- crime_00001 `generateInvoice` God Function (inner extraction) — separate change.\n- crime_00004 `direct_date` ×7 — clock injection comes after the split, per file.\n- crime_00007 `\"enterprise\"` literal scatter — touches 3 other files; out of scope.\n- crime_00008, crime_00011 — flagged above as natural follow-ups in `refunds.ts`.\n\nThe split is justified by `5 top-level functions` with clearly different responsibilities and **two duplicated rules** (tax, loyalty-age math) the scan already names — not by the 310 > 300 line count alone.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause\n\n**`crime_00004` — Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts`.** Seven direct reads of `Date.now()` / `new Date()` at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 — all inside the `generateInvoice` God Function (lines 50–253, `crime_00001`). Every call observes wall time at runtime, so any test that exercises billing-period math will flip behaviour at month/year/DST/UTC boundaries depending on *when* the suite runs. `src/date.ts` (`crime_00005`) has the same problem and is presumably what `billing.ts` is calling into, so the rot is on both sides of the boundary.\n\nTwo amplifiers explain why this isn't already caught:\n- `crime_00006` — `\"renders the enterprise plan\"` has **zero** assertions, so it can't fail no matter what date hits it.\n- `crime_00016` — `\"creates an invoice\"` uses only weak matchers, so it passes on any object-shaped output, masking off-by-one period math.\n\nCombined: real date bugs slip through because the tests don't assert the values that would change at a boundary, and the production code reads the clock seven times in one function so reproducing the failure locally is a coin flip.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\n1. **Inject a clock.** Add a `Clock` interface (`now(): Date`) and thread it through `generateInvoice` (and the helpers in `src/date.ts`). Default to a `systemClock` in production, pass a `fixedClock(new Date('2026-02-28T23:59:59Z'))` in tests. Replace all 7 sites in `billing.ts` and 5 in `date.ts`.\n2. **Pin the failing boundary in a new test** *before* changing the code — e.g. invoice generated at `2026-02-28T23:59:59.500Z` for a monthly plan should still bill February, not March. Use the injected clock so it's deterministic.\n3. **Strengthen `creates an invoice`** to assert the period start/end dates, not just truthiness — otherwise the regression that's flaking today walks back in tomorrow.\n4. **Don't extract `generateInvoice` in the same change.** The God Function (`crime_00001`) is the right next refactor, but doing it concurrently with a clock injection makes the diff unreviewable and risks a different bug. Land the clock fix, then split.\n\nStep 1 is the minimum to make the boundary test deterministic; steps 2–3 are what keep it from regressing. The God Function and the `enterprise` literal scatter (`crime_00007`) are real but unrelated to this bug — separate PRs.",
