/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Review verdict: hold for changes\n\nRubric I'm applying:\n- **Block** — sev ≥ 0.7, **or** sev ≥ 0.5 with agent_risk ≥ 0.5 in a safety-critical area (billing/refund logic).\n- **Warn** — sev ≥ 0.4 or agent_risk ≥ 0.5: worth fixing, not a merge blocker on its own.\n- **Ignore** — sev < 0.3 and agent_risk < 0.5: noise on this PR; address opportunistically.\n\n## Block merge (3)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk | Why block |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 00001 | God Function `generateInvoice` (204 LOC) | 0.90 / 0.63 | Only `high` finding. 3.4× the domain-function threshold inside billing. Future agent edits to one branch will silently miss interactions in another — exactly the failure mode `agent_risk` is meant to flag. |\n| 00004 | Temporal Recklessness in `src/billing.ts` (7 clock reads) | 0.60 / 0.53 | Wall-clock reads scattered through invoice generation. Tests can't pin time without monkey-patching, and the file has no real assertions to fall back on. In billing this is invoice-correctness risk, not style. |\n| 00008 | False Identity `calculateRefundPreview` | 0.55 / 0.52 | Name says pure preview, body calls `saveRefundAudit` + `sendRefundEmail`. Refund side effects under a \"preview\" verb is the kind of mislabelling that causes double-refunds when an agent calls it speculatively. Promoted to block on domain (refunds + audit trail). |\n\n## Warn — fix before next release, don't block this merge (14)\n\nHigher-impact warnings (sev ≥ 0.5 **or** agent_risk ≥ 0.55):\n\n- **00002** Missing Agent Context (0.60 / 0.61) — repo-level, predates this PR; flag to follow up.\n- **00005** Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (0.60 / 0.61) — utility module, lower blast than 00004 but same fix.\n- **00007** \"enterprise\" literal in 4 files (0.50 / 0.60) — duplicated policy risk; centralise before a 5th copy lands.\n- **00009** Concept Alias Drift (account/organisation/tea