\\\"report_type\\\": \\\"scan\\\",\\n  \\\"repo\\\": {\\n    \\\"name\\\": \\\"08-stress-dependency\\\",\\n    \\\"root\\\": \\\"/Users/andrew/dev/crimes/evals/fixtures/08-stress-dependency\\\"\\n  },\\n  \\\"summary\\\": {\\n    \\\"total\\\": 0,\\n    \\\"high\\\": 0,\\n    \\\"medium\\\": 0,\\n    \\\"low\\\": 0\\n  },\\n  \\\"findings\\\": []\\n}\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_11\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"`crimes scan --format json` did **not** report the cycle:\\n\\n```json\\n\\\"summary\\\": { \\\"total\\\": 0 },\\n\\\"findings\\\": []\\n```\\n\\nBut the fixture source has a clear circular import:\\n\\n`presentation/invoice-view.ts` -> `application/billing-flow.ts` -> `domain/billing.ts` -> `presentation/invoice-view.ts`\\n\\nThe import to break is:\\n\\n```ts\\n// src/domain/billing.ts\\nimport { renderInvoice } from \\\"../presentation/invoice-view.js\\\";\\n```\\n\\nThat is the wrong dependency direction. Domain code should not import presentation/UI code. Move invoice rendering out of `chargeCustomer`, or pass a formatter/render callback into the application layer. The domain should return billing data or a domain result; `presentation` can render it afterward.\\n\\nSo the likely fix is: make `chargeCustomer(amount)` return a domain value, and let `invoice-view.ts` call `renderInvoice` without the domain depending on it. This breaks the cycle at the layer violation and keeps the architecture direction clean.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":77781,\"cached_input_tokens\":69120,\"output_tokens\":992,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":131}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.2-r2/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Decompose `generateInvoice` (crime_00001, reinforced by crime_00010)\nThe 204-line `generateInvoice` (lines 50–253) is the highest-severity finding in the whole scan: `severity 0.9`, `agent_risk 0.63`, 3.4× the 60-line domain-function threshold. It's also the dominant reason the file as a whole crossed the 300-line God File threshold (crime_00010). Extract cohesive sections (line-item building, tax/discount, totals, persistence/notify) into named helpers. Doing this once collapses *two* findings and gives every other refactor below a smaller surface to work against — so it goes first.\n\n## 2. Inject a clock (crime_00004)\nSeven direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls at lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 make the billing pipeline non-deterministic and force any test to monkey-patch wall time. `test_gap 0.5` and a single weak-assertion test in `billing.test.ts` (crime_00006, crime_00016) say the safety net is already thin — every clock read in domain code makes it harder to add a real one. Thread a `now(): Date` (or `Clock`) through the call sites surfaced in step 1; the extraction makes the injection mechanical instead of invasive.\n\n## 3. Fix the refund seam: rename `calculateRefundPreview` *and* encode the comment rule (crime_00008 + crime_00011)\nThese two findings sit on adjacent lines (39 and 40–44) and describe the same hazard from two angles:\n- `calculateRefundPreview` reads as pure (`agent_risk 0.52`) but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail` — an agent will treat it as side-effect-free and call it speculatively.\n- The authorization rule *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* lives in a comment, not in code (`agent_risk 0.5`).\n\nSplit into a pure `previewRefund(...)` and an explicit `executeRefund(...)`, and lift the owner/billing-support check into a named guard (e.g. `assertCanRefund(actor, plan)`) with a test. That converts the most agent-hostile spot in the file — a load-bearing prose rule guarded by a misleadingly-named function — into something a coding agent can actually see.\n\n---\n\nDeferred deliberately: the `\"enterprise\"` literal scatter (crime_00007) and the 4 TODOs (crime_00020) are real but lower-leverage; they're easier to handle once the function is decomposed and the refund seam is honest.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.0/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e377b-df1b-73b1-8476-76917e0854fe\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: `crime_00004` / `direct_date` in [src/billing.ts](src/billing.ts), especially because the failure is date-boundary-related.\\n\\nThe scan says `billing.ts` reads wall time directly in 7 places: `Date.now()` and `new Date()` on lines `57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273`. That makes tests depend on the exact instant they run. Around midnight, month end, trial expiry, invoice cutoff, or timezone boundaries, two calls made milliseconds apart can land on different logical billing days.\\n\\nProposed fix: inject a clock into the billing code and use one captured `now` value per operation.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\nexport type Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nexport const systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n```\\n\\nThen billing functions should accept a clock, defaulting to `systemClock`:\\n\\n```ts\\nexport function createInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // use `now` everywhere in this operation\\n}\\n```\\n\\nTests can then pin the boundary:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-01-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\ncreateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n```\\n\\nI would fix this before chasing the weaker test findings. The weak tests explain why the bug escaped; the direct clock reads are the likely source of the flakiness.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":24630,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":346,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":22}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/refactor-01-plural-mismatch.json:7:  "response": "The scan turned up **one** `singular_plural_type_mismatch` finding (`crime_00034`) covering two declarations in `src/api/state.ts`. Both are unambiguous because the file already includes correctly-named negative controls (`user: User` @L33, `invoices: Invoice[]` @L34) — those tell us which side is load-bearing in each case.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `users: User` @L24\n\nEvidence (verbatim):\n> `plural name, singular type: ``users: User`` @L24`\n\n```ts\nexport const users: User = { id: \"u_1\", email: \"a@b.c\" };\n```\n\nThe initializer is a single object literal (`{ id, email }`), not an array — so the **type carries the intended meaning**. The variable holds one user; the plural name is the lie.\n\n**Proposal (a) — rename to match the type:**\n```ts\nexport const user1: User = { id: \"u_1\", email: \"a@b.c\" };\n// or simply merge with the existing `user` const on L33\n```\nA bare `user` would collide with line 33, which is why I'd suggest a disambiguating suffix or just removing this declaration if the L33 one is canonical.\n\nProposal (b) — change the type to match the name — would require fabricating a second element from nothing and rewriting the initializer. The shape of the value is the source of truth here, so go with (a).\n\n---\n\n### 2. `invoice: Invoice[]` @L27\n\nEvidence (verbatim):\n> `singular name, array type: ``invoice: Invoice[]`` @L27`\n\n```ts\nexport const invoice: Invoice[] = [];\n```\n\nThe annotation is `Invoice[]` and the initializer is `[]` — the array shape is committed to on both the type and the value side. The **type carries the intended meaning**; the singular name is the lie. The negative control on L34 (`export const invoices: Invoice[] = []`) confirms `invoices` is the project's chosen name for this shape.\n\n**Proposal (a) — rename to match the type:**\n```ts\nexport const invoices: Invoice[] = [];\n// collides with L34 — delete one, since they're identical\n```\n\nProposal (b) — collapsing `Invoice[]` to `Invoice` — would force `= []` to become a single `Invoice` object, which contradicts both the empty-array initializer and the existence of the `invoices` const right below it. Go with (a).\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Decl | Intended meaning lives in | Fix |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `users: User` @L24 | the type (single user, object initializer) | rename → singular (`user`, deduped against L33) |\n| `invoice: Invoice[]` @L27 | the type (array, `[]` initializer, mirrors L34) | rename → plural (`invoices`, deduped against L34) |\n\nIn both cases the **rename** is the right move — the value shape and the adjacent negative controls make the type the source of truth.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/refactor-08-architecture.json:7:  "response": "## Findings to address\n\n**crime_00002 — layer_violation** (`severity: medium`, `agent_risk: 0.63`)\n`src/domain/billing.ts` → `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`. Violates `domain cannotImport presentation`.\n\n**crime_00003 — deep_import** (`severity: low`, `agent_risk: 0.52`)\n`src/application/billing-flow.ts` → `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`.\n\n(Both are entangled with crime_00001 — the layer_violation edge is one of the three sides of the import cycle.)\n\n## Proposed changes\n\n### 1. Break: `domain/billing.ts` → `presentation/invoice-view.ts` (ties to crime_00002)\n\nThe domain layer must not know how an invoice is rendered. Two cases, pick by what's actually being imported:\n\n- **If the import is a type only** → convert to `import type { ... } from \"../presentation/invoice-view\"` so it carries no runtime edge. Cheap, but a code smell — the type probably belongs in domain.\n- **If the import is a value (function/class)** → apply dependency inversion. Define the contract in domain:\n  ```ts\n  // src/domain/invoice-renderer.ts\n  export interface InvoiceRenderer { render(invoice: Invoice): string }\n  ```\n  `presentation/invoice-view.ts` implements it; `application/billing-flow.ts` wires the concrete implementation into the domain caller. Domain now points outward only through an interface it owns.\n\nThis single change also collapses the cycle in crime_00001, because the cycle's domain→presentation edge is the same edge.\n\n### 2. Redirect: `application/billing-flow.ts` deep import (ties to crime_00003)\n\nReplace `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js` with `some-pkg`'s public entry:\n\n```ts\nimport { helper } from \"some-pkg\"   // if exported\n```\n\nIf the symbol isn't on the public surface, the suggested action is right: file an upstream issue rather than locking us to a private path. Do **not** wrap the deep import in a local re-export — that just hides the same coupling behind one more file.\n\n## How the two findings differ in agent risk\n\nBoth score `test_gap: 1` and identical `blast_radius`, so the gap between 0.63 and 0.52 is almost entirely **severity** — and severity here is shorthand for *who gets misled and how*.\n\n- **Layer violation is a directional invariant inside our code.** An agent reading `domain/billing.ts` and seeing a presentation import will reasonably conclude that \"domain depends on presentation\" is allowed, and will propagate that pattern on the next change. It inverts the intended direction of change for the whole codebase, not just this file. That's why it scores higher despite being \"only\" medium severity.\n- **Deep import is a coupling to code we don't own.** The blast radius inside *our* repo is small — one file, one import — and an agent editing this file isn't going to mis-learn an architectural rule from it. The real risk is silent breakage on a `some-pkg` upgrade, which is a temporal/maintenance risk, not a confusion-propagation risk. Lower agent risk, correctly.\n\nShort version: layer_violation teaches the wrong lesson; deep_import is a tripwire that hasn't tripped yet.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/refactor-01-large-file.json:7:  "response": "## Plan to split `src/billing.ts` — anchored to `large_file` (crime_00016)\n\n**The evidence**: 310 non-empty lines (1.0× the 300 threshold) and **5 top-level functions** — those 5 functions are the natural unit of split, and three of them (`generateInvoice`, `tax`, `recommendUpgrade`) hide duplicated logic that the current file lets drift silently. Co-located findings pin the seams:\n\n| Evidence anchor | Tells us |\n|---|---|\n| `crime_00002` — `generateInvoice` is 204 lines (L50–253) | One function is **~65% of the file**; relocating it alone drops the parent under threshold. |\n| `crime_00013` + `crime_00017` — `calculateRefundPreview` does side-effects, and the **prose rule** at L39 (\"only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\") sits orphaned above it | Refund is a distinct concern from invoice generation, and the policy currently lives in a comment that no code enforces. |\n| `crime_00009` — 7 `Date` calls scattered across L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 | Clock access threads through **multiple functions** — extracting per-function won't fix it; needs a shared seam. |\n| Duplicated tax table at L145–154 vs `tax()` at L257–268; duplicated `daysSince` loyalty math at L92 vs `recommendUpgrade` at L273 | These are the cohesion seams — pulling tax and pricing into their own modules forces the duplicate copies to converge. |\n\n### Proposed file layout\n\n```\nsrc/billing/\n  types.ts        // L4–31 — User, InvoiceLine, Invoice interfaces\n  refund.ts       // L40–44 calculateRefundPreview + the L39 rule encoded as a guard\n  tax.ts          // L257–268 tax() + the country→rate table currently duplicated at L147–154\n  pricing.ts      // L66–126: plan adjustments, loyalty discount, promo resolution, currency\n  risk.ts         // L128–143 fraud-risk scoring\n  invoice.ts      // L50–253 generateInvoice — now an orchestrator that calls pricing/tax/risk\n  upgrade.ts      // L272–305 recommendUpgrade\n  index.ts        // barrel re-exporting the public surface\n```\n\n(`listRecentInvoices` at L307–310 is a TODO stub — keep it in `invoice.ts` or delete; not worth its own file.)\n\n### Order of operations (each step lands under green tests)\n\n1. **`types.ts` first.** Pure move of L4–31. No behaviour change. Everything else will import from it.\n2. **`tax.ts` second.** Move L257–268. *Then* replace the duplicated table at L145–154 inside `generateInvoice` with `tax(user.country, afterDiscount)`. This is the smallest split that erases a duplicate (`crime_00016` evidence: 5 top-level fns → 4 after, and the duplicate vanishes).\n3. **`refund.ts` third.** Move `calculateRefundPreview` *and* convert the L39 comment into a guard (`canRefund(user, invoice)` — addresses `crime_00017`). Rename to disclose the side effects per `crime_00013` (e.g. `previewAndRecordRefund` or split pure preview from `recordRefundAudit`/`sendRefundEmail`).\n4. **`pricing.ts` + `risk.ts`.** Extract the labelled sections inside `generateInvoice` (the L66 / L91 / L105 / L128 comment-banners are already the section boundaries the original author drew). `generateInvoice` becomes the orchestrator. This is where the `large_function` charge (`crime_00002`) actually resolves — but it's a separate refactor, scheduled here because once it's out of `billing.ts` the parent finding drops well below threshold without touching it.\n5. **`upgrade.ts`.** Move `recommendUpgrade`. While moving it, replace its inline `daysSince` math (L273) with a shared `daysSince(user)` helper alongside the loyalty math in `pricing.ts` — the duplicate `(Date.now() - user.createdAt) / (1000*60*60*24)` at L92 and L273 was a smell that a same-file reader rarely sees.\n6. **`index.ts` barrel.** Re-export the public surface — but only the symbols actually imported elsewhere.\n\n### Callers to update\n\n`grep -rn \"from.*billing\"` across `src/` returns **zero hits** — nothing in the repo imports `src/billing.ts` today. `src/billing.test.ts` uses local stubs (`renderEnterprisePlan`, `createInvoice`), not the real exports (and is the subject of `crime_00011` / `crime_00030` weak-test findings — worth fixing in the same PR but not blocking the split).\n\nSo caller churn is essentially:\n\n- **External imports**: none to update.\n- **Internal imports within the new `src/billing/` tree**: `invoice.ts` will import from `./pricing`, `./tax`, `./risk`, `./types`; `refund.ts` and `upgrade.ts` import from `./types`.\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`**: should be rewritten to actually call the new modules (separate concern, but the split makes that possible — right now the test stubs avoid the file because the file is too tangled to test).\n\n### What this plan deliberately does **not** do\n\n- Doesn't touch `crime_00009` (clock injection) as part of the split — that's a cross-cutting change that should land *after* the modules exist, so the clock seam can be added in one place each (`pricing.ts`, `invoice.ts`, `upgrade.ts`) rather than threaded through one 310-line file. Splits first; clock seam second.\n- Doesn't try to fix `generateInvoice`'s internal God-Function structure (`crime_00002`) in the same PR — step 4 *enables* that work by giving it a target module, but extracting helpers inside `invoice.ts` is a separate, reviewable change.\n- Doesn't centralise the `\"enterprise\"` literal (`crime_00012`) yet — that's a cross-file fix; this PR only splits one file.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Review verdict — review-01-messy-ts-app\n\nTotal: **37 findings** (4 high, 15 medium, 18 low) over an empty baseline. Treating this as a single PR that introduces everything at once.\n\n## 🛑 Block merge (7)\n\nFindings that either don't work outside the author's machine, encode a real correctness bug, or carry enough agent-risk that landing them sets a bad precedent for the repo's first commit.\n\n| ID | Charge | Why block |\n|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00007` | Localhost-on-Disk (`/Users/andrew/…`) — med, agent_risk 0.61 | Severity rating understates impact: this literal **cannot work** for any other dev, CI runner, or deploy. Fix is one line. |\n| `crime_00006` | Dev-Server URL (`localhost:3000`) — med, agent_risk 0.61 | Same class of bug: silently fails in every non-local environment. Must be env-driven before merge. |\n| `crime_00004` | Half-UTC, Half-Local — **high**, agent_risk 0.68 | An actual correctness bug — same receiver `d` mixes `getUTCFullYear()` and `getMonth()`, will skew by the host's TZ offset. |\n| `crime_00010` | Timezone Roulette — med, agent_risk 0.61 | `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` and `\"2026-12-20\"` parse against host TZ. With `crime_00004` in the same file, the date module is unfixable until both are resolved. |\n| `crime_00011` | Test That Proves Nothing — med, agent_risk 0.46 | Zero `expect` calls in \"renders the enterprise plan\". A test that asserts nothing is worse than no test; it creates false confidence for human reviewers and agents alike. |\n| `crime_00002` | God Function `generateInvoice` (204 lines) — **high**, agent_risk 0.63 | 3.4× the threshold, sitting in a billing module. Any agent edit later is a coin-flip; better to split before this lands than to retrofit it after callers form around it. |\n| `crime_00013` | `calculateRefundPreview` does refunds & emails — med, agent_risk 0.52 | Name promises pure preview, body calls `saveRefundAudit` + `sendRefundEmail`. This is exactly the kind of foot-gun an agent will pull mid-flight. |\n\n## ⚠️ Warn (15)\n\nReal issues — author should fix before or shortly after merge, but they don't block a first-pass review.\n\n| ID | Charge | Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00001` | SVG With Embedded Raster — **high**, agent_risk 0.7 | High severity but cosmetic; warn unless asset is in the rendering hot path. |\n| `crime_00003` | Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (8 calls) — **high**, agent_risk 0.69 | The whole module needs a clock abstraction; flag as a follow-up issue rather than blocking this PR. |\n| `crime_00009` | Temporal Recklessness in `billing.ts` (7 calls) — med, agent_risk 0.53 | Same class of fix; track with `crime_00003`. |\n| `crime_00005` | Missing Agent Context — med, agent_risk 0.61 | Add `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md` before more agent work lands; non-blocking for the code itself. |\n| `crime_00014` | DST-Naive Day Math (`+ 86400000`) — med, agent_risk 0.59 | Real bug class but isolated to one line; fix in the date-module follow-up. |\n| `crime_00017` | Logic in the Alibi (refund auth rule in a comment) — med, agent_risk 0.5 | Encode the rule next to or after the refund refactor (`crime_00013`). |\n| `crime_00012` | \"enterprise\" literal across 4 files — med, agent_risk 0.6 | Centralise before the 5th copy appears. |\n| `crime_00015` | Tenant/account/organisation/team/workspace drift — med, agent_risk 0.58 | Pick the canonical noun before adding more routes. |\n| `crime_00018` | Duplicated Nav Source (`Plans` vs `Billing`) — med, agent_risk 0.57 | Pairs with `crime_00020`; fix together. |\n| `crime_00020` | Route Metadata Drift on `/settings/billing` — med, agent_risk 0.56 | Four names for one destination; align in the nav cleanup. |\n| `crime_00019` | TODO density in `src/todo.ts` (14 markers in 33 lines) — med, agent_risk 0.57 | This is mostly a fixture artefact, but if it's intended to ship, triage before merging. |\n| `crime_00016` | God File `billing.ts` (310 lines) — med, agent_risk 0.5 | Just past the threshold; will follow from splitting `generateInvoice`. |\n| `crime_00021` | Oversized Raster (253 KB hero) — low, agent_risk 0.52 | Page-weight concern; cheap to fix. |\n| `crime_00022` | Docs-Code Drift (`./setup.md` missing) — low, agent_risk 0.51 | Fix the link or restore the file. |\n| `crime_00023` | Sync I/O in Hot Path (3 `*Sync` calls in `loadPlanSchema`) — low, agent_risk 0.51 | Confidence 0.9 — clear async swap, but blast_radius is 0 here. |\n\n## 🤫 Ignore for this PR (15)\n\nLow severity AND agent_risk ≤ 0.51. Stylistic, ergonomic, or local — accumulate them on a backlog ticket, don't gate this merge.\n\n| ID | Charge | Why ignore |\n|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00024` | Temporal Recklessness — 1 `Date.now()` in `state.ts`, agent_risk 0.51 | Covered by the date-module follow-up. |\n| `crime_00025` | Icon-Sized Raster (32×32 check icon) — agent_risk 0.5 | Polish, not a risk. |\n| `crime_00026` | Date String Sewing — agent_risk 0.5 | Subsumed by the date-module fix. |\n| `crime_00027` | Host-Locale Drift (`toLocaleDateString()`) — agent_risk 0.5 | Same. |\n| `crime_00028` | Unprefixed booleans in `state.ts` — agent_risk 0.49 | Naming nit. |\n| `crime_00029` | Unprefixed booleans in `petty.ts` — agent_risk 0.49 | Same. |\n| `crime_00030` | Test with weak matcher (`creates an invoice`) — agent_risk 0.34 | Strengthen when the test next changes. |\n| `crime_00031` | Option-bag `describeCheckout` — agent_risk 0.48 | Type-shape nit. |\n| `crime_00032` | Return-shape roulette `resolvePaymentResult` — agent_risk 0.48 | Same. |\n| `crime_00033` | Negative-flag maze `!disableBilling && !skipRetry` — agent_risk 0.47 | Rename next time these flags change. |\n| `crime_00034` | Plural mismatch (`users: User`, `invoice: Invoice[]`) — agent_risk 0.47 | Likely a typo; one-line fix when convenient. |\n| `crime_00035` | TODO density in `billing.ts` (just over threshold) — agent_risk 0.4 | Triage