/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Most likely cause\n\n**`crime_00004` — Half-UTC, Half-Local in `src/date.ts`** is the smoking gun. The same `d` receiver is read with `getUTCFullYear()` at L9 and `getMonth()` (local) at L41. Those two families disagree by the host's UTC offset on exactly the boundary cases that flake — late-evening or early-morning instants where the UTC date and local date differ.\n\nTwo related findings amplify it:\n\n- **`crime_00010` — Timezone Roulette** at `src/date.ts:29,33`: `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` and `new Date(\"2026-12-20\")` parse with no zone. The first uses host-local time; the second uses UTC. So the *same literal-looking code path* yields different absolute instants depending on which constructor branch runs, and the resulting `Date` is then fed to the mixed UTC/local readers above.\n- **`crime_00014` — DST-Naive Day Math** at `src/date.ts:52`: `+ 86400000` for \"one day\". On DST-transition days the result is off by an hour, which is enough to flip the local date when the original instant is near midnight.\n\n`crime_00009` (7 direct `Date.now()`/`new Date()` in `billing.ts`) is why the failure is *flaky* rather than constant — wall time supplies the boundary instant that exposes the bug.\n\n# Proposed fix\n\nOrder by leverage, smallest blast radius first:\n\n1. **`src/date.ts:9 & 41` — unify the family on `d`.** Pick UTC throughout the function (it's already using `getUTCFullYear`) and change `getMonth()` → `getUTCMonth()`. This alone should stabilize the boundary tests if the bug is the local/UTC split on a single receiver.\n2. **`src/date.ts:29,33` — make the literals explicit.** Append `Z` (or a `±HH:MM` offset matching the business intent) to `\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` and `\"2026-12-20\"`. Document which one is meant.\n3. **`src/date.ts:52` — replace `+ 86400000` with a calendar-aware `addDays`** (Temporal, Luxon, or date-fns-tz). Required for any boundary that crosses a DST shift.\n4. **Then** address the temporal coupling: inject a `Clock` / `now()` into `generateInvoice` (`crime_00009`) so the test can pin the instant and the bug becomes reproducible instead of flaky. This is the real long-term fix — without it you're patching symptoms.\n\nThe minimal change that should turn the test green is step 1. Steps 2–3 close adjacent boundary bugs the same test set is likely to hit next. Step 4 is the durable fix.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.15/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Break up `generateInvoice` (crime_00002, knocks down crime_00016)\n\n204 lines spanning L50–253 — 3.4× the domain threshold and the single highest-severity finding in the file (severity 0.9). It's also the reason the file as a whole trips God File at 310 lines; carve cohesive sections out of `generateInvoice` and the file shrinks below the 300-line line by construction. Extract along responsibility seams (line-item assembly, tax/proration, persistence, notification) so an agent editing one section can't silently break the others.\n\n## 2. Encode the L39 comment rule and rename `calculateRefundPreview` (crime_00017 + crime_00013)\n\nThese are the same bug wearing two hats. The comment at L39 — *\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\"* — is a policy the surrounding code doesn't visibly enforce, and the function it precedes (`calculateRefundPreview`, L40–44) lies about itself: a \"preview\" / \"calculate\" name that actually calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. An agent reads the name, assumes pure, and ships an edit that double-charges audit rows or fires a second email. Fix by (a) extracting the role/plan check into a named guard (`assertCanRefundEnterprise(actor, plan)`) so the rule lives in code, and (b) splitting the function into `buildRefundPreview` (pure) + `commitRefund` (the audit + email side effects). This also gives the still-empty tests in `src/billing.test.ts` (crime_00011) something real to assert against.\n\n## 3. Inject a clock for the 7 `Date` calls in billing (crime_00009)\n\nSeven direct `Date.now()` / `new Date()` calls across L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273. Invoice generation that reads wall-time is what's keeping the existing tests weak — \"renders the enterprise plan\" asserts nothing (crime_00011) and \"creates an invoice\" only uses a weak matcher (crime_00030) because there's no way to pin a stable `issuedAt`/`dueAt` without monkey-patching globals. Thread a `clock: () => Date` (or `now: () => number`) parameter through `generateInvoice` and its new helpers from step 1; default it to `Date.now` at the CLI/API boundary. Once invoice timestamps are deterministic, the tests can assert exact totals, due dates, and proration without flake — and the shared `src/date.ts` cluster (crime_00003, _00004, _00010, _00014) becomes the next obvious thing to clean up using the same clock seam.",
