daries. Smaller modules give humans and agents a smaller surface to reason about per edit.\\\",\\n          \\\"risk\\\": \\\"medium\\\"\\n        }\\n      ]\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"id\\\": \\\"crime_00006\\\",\\n      \\\"type\\\": \\\"logic_in_comments\\\",\\n      \\\"charge\\\": \\\"Logic in the Alibi\\\",\\n      \\\"severity\\\": \\\"medium\\\",\\n      \\\"confidence\\\": 0.71,\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"src/billing.ts\\\",\\n      \\\"lines\\\": [\\n        39,\\n        39\\n      ],\\n      \\\"summary\\\": \\\"Comment appears to carry a rule that nearby code does not obviously encode. Hidden prose rules are easy for agents and new maintainers to miss.\\\",\\n      \\\"evidence\\\": [\\n        \\\"comment says: \\\\\\\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.\\\\\\\"\\\",\\n        \\\"rule terms: only, unless\\\",\\n        \\\"domain terms not found nearby: owner, plan, billing\\\"\\n      ],\\n      \\\"scores\\\": {\\n        \\\"severity\\\": 0.5,\\n        \\\"confidence\\\": 0.71,\\n        \\\"agent_risk\\\": 0.53,\\n        \\\"churn\\\": 0.2,\\n        \\\"test_gap\\\": 0.5,\\n        \\\"blast_radius\\\": 0\\n      },\\n      \\\"suggested_actions\\\": [\\n        {\\n          \\\"kind\\\": \\\"encode_comment_rule\\\",\\n          \\\"description\\\": \\\"Move the rule into a named guard, type, config value, or test; keep comments for rationale.\\\",\\n          \\\"risk\\\": \\\"low\\\"\\n        }\\n      ]\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"id\\\": \\\"crime_00007\\\",\\n      \\\"type\\\": \\\"todo_density\\\",\\n      \\\"charge\\\": \\\"Unfinished Business\\\",\\n      \\\"severity\\\": \\\"low\\\",\\n      \\\"confidence\\\": 0.7,\\n      \\\"file\\\": \\\"src/billing.ts\\\",\\n      \\\"lines\\\": [\\n        183,\\n        308\\n      ],\\n      \\\"summary\\\": \\\"4 TODO/FIXME markers (12.9 per 1k LOC). Each marker is intended behaviour the author flagged as not-final — too many in one file makes it hard for an agent to tell which logic is load-bearing.\\\",\\n      \\\"evidence\\\": [\\n        \\\"1× FIXME, 1× HACK, 1× XXX, 1× TODO\\\",\\n        \\\"12.9 markers per 1k LOC (threshold 10)\\\"\\n      ],\\n      \\\"scores\\\": {\\n        \\\"severity\\\": 0.2,\\n        \\\"confidence\\\": 0.7,\\n        \\\"agent_risk\\\": 0.43,\\n        \\\"churn\\\": 0.2,\\n        \\\"test_gap\\\": 0.5,\\n        \\\"blast_radius\\\": 0\\n      },\\n      \\\"suggested_actions\\\": [\\n        {\\n          \\\"kind\\\": \\\"triage_todos\\\",\\n          \\\"description\\\": \\\"Convert each marker into a tracked issue or remove it. Lingering TODOs mislead humans and agents about which behaviour is intentional.\\\",\\n          \\\"risk\\\": \\\"low\\\"\\n        }\\n      ]\\n    }\\n  ],\\n  \\\"suppressed_count\\\": 1\\n}\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_2\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Top 3 changes I’d make in `src/billing.ts`:\\n\\n1. Extract `generateInvoice` into focused helpers.\\n   Finding: `crime_00001`, `large_function`, high severity. `generateInvoice` is 204 lines, 3.4x the domain threshold. This is the main risk reducer because invoice generation likely mixes pricing, discounts, tax, payment state, messaging, and side effects. I’d first extract pure helpers around cohesive sections, then cover those helpers through `src/billing.test.ts`.\\n\\n2. Inject time instead of calling `Date.now()` / `new Date()` directly.\\n   Finding: `crime_00003`, `direct_date`, medium severity. There are 7 direct clock reads on lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, and 273. This makes billing behavior hard to pin in tests. I’d add a small `Clock`/`now` dependency and thread it through `generateInvoice` and any billing helper that needs time.\\n\\n3. Split the misleading refund preview behavior into pure calculation plus side effects.\\n   Findings: `crime_00004` and `crime_00006`. `calculateRefundPreview` sounds pure but calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`; nearby prose also says “Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves” without an obvious encoded guard. I’d extract a pure `calculateRefundPreview` result, move auditing/email into an explicit command-style function, and encode the owner/support approval rule as a named predicate with tests.\\n\\nI’d treat `crime_00005` (`large_file`) as a follow-on once those extractions reveal clean module boundaries. The file is only barely over threshold, so splitting it before reducing `generateInvoice` would be less valuable.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":54390,\"cached_input_tokens\":38144,\"output_tokens\":502,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":20}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/context-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## What `src/billing.ts` does\n\nIt's a 310-line domain module centred on **`generateInvoice`** (204 lines, lines 50–253) plus a misleadingly-named **`calculateRefundPreview`** (lines 40–44) that actually performs side effects (`saveRefundAudit`, `sendRefundEmail`). The file declares 5 top-level functions and works heavily with the `\"enterprise\"` plan concept and wall-clock time (7 direct `Date.now()`/`new Date()` calls).\n\n## Files I'd also need to read\n\n- **`src/date.ts`** — billing's date helpers live here, and the scan flags it as the epicentre of temporal bugs (UTC/local mixing, unsafe `new Date(\"…\")` parses, DST-naive `+86400000` math, host-locale drift). Anything `generateInvoice` does with dates is probably routed through this file.\n- **`src/api/plan.ts`, `src/jobs/plan-sync.ts`, `src/ui/pricing.ts`** — all three repeat the `\"enterprise\"` literal (crime_00009). Plan policy is duplicated across them; editing billing without checking these risks divergent policy.\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** — exists but the suite is hollow: one test has zero assertions (crime_00008), another only uses weak matchers (crime_00021). Don't trust green tests here.\n- **Whatever defines `saveRefundAudit` / `sendRefundEmail` and the owner/billing-support permission check** — the comment at line 39 encodes a rule (\"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\") that the surrounding code doesn't obviously implement (crime_00014).\n\n## Risks flagged for `src/billing.ts`\n\n| Severity | Charge | Where | Why it matters for an editor |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **high** | God Function | `generateInvoice` L50–253 (204 lines, 3.4× threshold) | Mixed responsibilities — an edit in one section likely interacts with code you didn't load. |\n| medium | Temporal Recklessness | 7× `Date.now()`/`new Date()` at L57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273 | Non-deterministic; tests can't pin a fixed moment. |\n| medium | False Identity | `calculateRefundPreview` L40–44 | \"Preview\" name but performs audit + email side effects — callers may assume purity. |\n| medium | God File | whole file, 310 LOC | At threshold; hidden local coupling. |\n| medium | Logic in the Alibi | comment at L39 | Refund authorisation rule lives only in prose. |\n| low | Unfinished Business | 4 markers L183–308 (FIXME/HACK/XXX/TODO) | Hard to tell which logic is load-bearing. |\n\nPlus the cross-cutting hits that touch billing: the scattered `\"enterprise\"` literal (crime_00009) and the absence of any `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` (crime_00004) — meaning conventions aren't discoverable before editing.\n\n**Before editing**: read `src/date.ts` and the three `\"enterprise\"`-referencing files alongside `billing.ts`, treat the existing tests as non-protective, and clarify the owner/billing-support refund rule from L39 before touching `calculateRefundPreview` or any refund path inside `generateInvoice`.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "## Most likely cause: `src/date.ts` mixes UTC and local Date methods on the same receiver\n\nThe smoking gun is **crime_00003** (`Half-UTC, Half-Local`, severity high, confidence 0.85):\n\n> Receiver `d` in `src/date.ts` reads `getUTCFullYear()` at L9 **and** `getMonth()` at L41 — UTC year, local month.\n\nThat single mismatch is the textbook date-boundary flake. Around month/year rollover, the UTC year and the local month disagree by the host's UTC offset. Run the suite in UTC and it passes; run it at 17:00 PST on Dec 31 and the \"year\" comes from one frame, the \"month\" from another → invoice period straddles boundaries it shouldn't.\n\nTwo findings amplify it and explain why it shows up specifically on date boundaries:\n\n- **crime_00007** (`Timezone Roulette`, L29/L33): `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` and `new Date(\"2026-12-20\")` parse with no zone marker. ISO date-only strings are parsed as **UTC**; date-time strings without `Z` are parsed as **local**. So those two literals already live in different frames before anything reads them.\n- **crime_00011** (`DST-Naive`, L52): `+ 86400000` for day arithmetic. On DST transition days a \"day\" isn't 86,400,000 ms — silent ±1h drift that compounds with the UTC/local mix.\n\n`generateInvoice` (crime_00001/_00006) is downstream of these — it's where the symptoms surface, but it isn't the root cause. The 7 `Date.now()`/`new Date()` calls inside it make the tests *non-deterministic*, not *boundary-flaky*.\n\n## Proposed fix (in order)\n\n1. **`src/date.ts` L9 + L41** — pick one family for `d` and stick to it. For billing math, use UTC throughout: `d.getUTCMonth()` at L41 (and audit the rest of the receiver's reads). This is the actual bug.\n2. **L29, L33** — append `Z` to the literals (`\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\"`, `\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\"`) so parsing is unambiguous, or parse through a TZ-aware helper.\n3. **L52** — replace `+ 86400000` with a calendar-aware `addDays` (Luxon/Temporal/date-fns-tz). Eliminates the DST edge case.\n4. **Then** the temporal-recklessness findings (crime_00002, _00006): inject a clock into `generateInvoice` so the tests can pin a fixed instant and the boundary cases become reproducible rather than time-of-day-dependent.\n\nStep 1 alone will most likely turn the test green; steps 2–4 keep it from coming back the next time the calendar lands wrong.",
