/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/refactor-08-architecture.json:7:  "response": "## Changes to make\n\n**1. Break `domain/billing.ts` → `presentation/invoice-view.ts`** (ties to `crime_00002` layer_violation, and is also one edge of `crime_00001`'s cycle)\n\nThe domain layer must not know presentation exists. Two valid moves, depending on what's actually being imported:\n\n- **If domain is importing a *type* presentation owns** (e.g. a view-model shape): invert it. Define the shape in `domain/` as the canonical type, and have `presentation/invoice-view.ts` import *from* domain. The presentation layer is allowed to depend on domain.\n- **If domain is calling presentation behavior** (e.g. a formatter, a renderer hook): define an interface in `domain/` (e.g. `InvoicePresenter`) and have the application layer wire a concrete `invoice-view` implementation in. Domain depends on its own interface; presentation implements it. This is the dependency inversion the suggested_action gestures at.\n\nEither fix collapses the cycle as a side effect, because the offending edge (domain → presentation) is what closes the application → domain → presentation → application ring.\n\n**2. Redirect `application/billing-flow.ts` away from `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`** (ties to `crime_00003` deep_import)\n\nReplace the import with `some-pkg`'s documented entry — `import { ... } from \"some-pkg\"`. If the symbol you need isn't re-exported there, the right move is to file an upstream issue, not to deepen the coupling. As a stopgap, wrap the deep import in a single adapter module inside `application/` (or better, `infrastructure/`) so the fragile path lives in one file you can patch on upgrade, instead of being load-bearing in business logic.\n\n## Why `layer_violation` carries more agent risk than `deep_import` (0.63 vs 0.52)\n\nBoth are dependency crimes, but they mislead an agent in different ways:\n\n- **`layer_violation` lies about the architecture.** The repo declares a four-layer contract in `crimes.config.json` — that's a structural promise an agent uses to reason about blast radius. \"I'm editing `domain/billing.ts`, so changes flow outward toward callers.\" When domain secretly depends on presentation, that mental model is wrong: edits in domain can break the view, and edits in the view can break domain. The directory tree is now an unreliable guide to what depends on what. That's the agent-specific harm — an agent that trusts the stated layering will make unsafe edits with high confidence.\n\n- **`deep_import` is fragile but honest.** The specifier `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js` advertises its own crime on the line — anyone reading it (human or agent) can see it's reaching past a published surface. The risk is real but *contained and time-shifted*: a future package upgrade may quietly move or rename the internal, breaking this one file. The architecture isn't being lied about; one file is just hanging off a private branch.\n\nRoughly: `layer_violation` corrupts the map the agent navigates by, `deep_import` puts a single trapdoor on an otherwise correct map. The map being wrong is worse, so the score is higher.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/bugfix-08-stress-dependency.json:7:  "response": "## Break the `domain → presentation` edge\n\n`src/domain/billing.ts` → `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` is the import to remove.\n\n**Why this edge (not the other two):**\n\n1. **It's the only edge that's wrong on its own merits.** The scan flags it independently as a Layer Violation (`crime_00002`): `domain cannotImport presentation`. The other two edges in the cycle (presentation → application, application → domain) are *with* the conventional layering direction — presentation depends on application logic, application depends on domain. Breaking either of those would just relocate the architectural smell.\n2. **Two crimes collapse into one fix.** Cutting this edge resolves both the `circular_dependency` (high) and the `layer_violation` (medium) — the cycle exists *because* of the inversion. No other single edit does that.\n3. **Domain should be a sink, not a source.** Whatever symbol `billing.ts` is reaching into `invoice-view.ts` for is almost certainly a type, label, or formatting concern that belongs *in* the domain (or in a shared module), not in the view.\n\n**How to break it (in order of preference):**\n\n1. If it's only a type import → change to `import type { … }` so it contributes no runtime edge. Cheapest, zero behavior change.\n2. If it's a shared shape/constant → extract into a neutral module (e.g. `src/domain/invoice-types.ts`) that both `domain/billing.ts` and `presentation/invoice-view.ts` import from. Domain owns the contract; presentation conforms.\n3. If `domain/billing.ts` is actually calling presentation behavior → invert via an interface owned by domain (e.g. `InvoiceRenderer`), and have the presentation layer implement it. Application wires the implementation in.\n\nOption 1 is worth checking first — `import type` cycles are common and the fix is one keyword.\n\nSide note: `crime_00003` (deep import into `some-pkg/dist/internal/...`) is unrelated to the cycle and can be addressed separately.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/review-02-react-dashboard.json:7:  "response": "# Categorisation by detector\n\nNo finding is `high` severity and the maximum `agent_risk` is `0.62`, so nothing here clears a *block* bar on its own. Two structural signals before I categorise:\n\n1. **The dataset is dominated by tutorial fixtures.** `basics/*-starter` ↔ `basics/*-final`, `dashboard/starter-example` ↔ `dashboard/final-example`, `seo/` ↔ `seo/demo/` — these are deliberate parallel copies. A PR that lands this layout is shipping the layout itself, not duplicating production code. That makes most of the `exact_duplicate_block` findings noise *for this PR* even though the detector is correct.\n2. **What matters on top of an empty baseline is the policy/testability signal**, not the volume.\n\n---\n\n## `exact_duplicate_block` — 46 findings, severity `medium` (0.55), agent_risk `0.62`\n\n- **Ignore (40):** Cross-tutorial duplicates between `basics/*-starter` ↔ `basics/*-final` / `demo`, `dashboard/starter-example` ↔ `dashboard/final-example`, `seo/` ↔ `seo/demo/`. These pairs are tutorial step variants — the duplication *is* the artifact. Extracting a shared helper would defeat the fixture's purpose. Confidence in the detector is high (0.95) but the framing it implies (one helper, one fix-site) is wrong here. (`crime_00001`–`crime_00046` except the ones below.)\n- **Warn (none in this scan but worth calling out):** if any of these pairs had been inside a single `app/` tree (not `final-example` vs `starter-example`), I'd warn. None do.\n\n## `commented_out_code` — 10 findings (4× medium, 6× low)\n\n- **Warn (4× medium):** `crime_00047`–`crime_00050` — agent_risk `0.61`, severity `0.45`. These are 30–38 line dead JSX blocks in `latest-invoices.tsx`, `revenue-chart.tsx`, `pagination.tsx`, `query/route.ts`. Even if they're \"uncomment to enable\" tutorial scaffolding, that exact pattern is the highest-risk shape for an agent to either revive or cargo-cult. Ask the PR author to either delete or replace with a one-line rationale.\n- **Ignore (6× low):** `crime_00058`, `crime_00059`, `crime_00060`, `crime_00061`, `crime_00064`, `crime_00065` — agent_risk `0.49`–`0.51`, severity `0.25`. Short 2–8 line comment blocks with little semantic weight. Not worth a review round-trip.\n\n## `magic_domain_literal_scatter` — 1 finding, medium (0.5), agent_risk `0.6`\n\n- **Warn:** `crime_00051` — `\"status\"` appears across 5 invoice form / action files. This is exactly the kind of signal `crimes` exists to surface: a domain literal scattered across forms + server actions is one rename away from drifting. Author should centralise to a constant/enum before the next status field arrives.\n\n## `duplicate_component_shape` — 1 finding, medium (0.55), agent_risk `0.57`\n\n- **Warn:** `crime_00052` — same `<div>` subtree in 4 `create-form` / `edit-form` files. Lower confidence (0.7) than the exact-block detector, but it's pointing at the canonical \"extract a `<StatusRadio>` component\" smell. Worth flagging on the PR even if not blocking.\n\n## `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` — 2 findings, medium (0.55), agent_risk `0.57`\n\n- **Warn:** `crime_00053` (`\"pending\"`), `crime_00054` (`\"paid\"`). 4 files, 2 distinct expression shapes for each literal — `invoice.status === \"pending\"` in forms vs `status === \"pending\"` in `status.tsx`. This is policy drift waiting to happen and the highest-leverage thing to flag on this PR: one shared `isPaid()` / `isPending()` helper kills both findings and prevents future agents from inventing a third shape.\n\n## `direct_date` — 3 findings, severity `low` (0.35), agent_risk `0.51`\n\n- **Warn (1):** `crime_00055` — `new Date()` in `app/lib/actions.ts:57`. This is a server action; non-determinism here makes tests flaky and couples behaviour to wall time. Suggest injecting a `now()`.\n- **Ignore (2):** `crime_00056`, `crime_00057` — both in `app/lib/utils.ts:14` (`formatDateToLocal`-style helpers). Wall-clock reads inside a pure formatter are fine; the detector can't distinguish \"domain code\" from \"format helper\" without more context.\n\n## `deep_import` — 2 findings, low (0.35), agent_risk `0.5`\n\n- **Ignore:** `crime_00062`, `crime_00063` — `react-syntax-highlighter/dist/cjs/styles/prism` is the *documented* way to load that package's styles. Detector is correct that it's a deep import; the suggested fix (use the public entry) doesn't apply for this library. Suppress at config level if it keeps recurring.\n\n## `design_token_escape` — 8 findings, low (0.4), agent_risk `0.48`\n\n- **Ignore (all 8):** `crime_00066`–`crime_00073`. Inline `px` values in tutorial forms and skeletons. With no design-token system established in this fixture, the detector has nothing to compare against — flagging here is premature optimisation. Worth revisiting once a `tokens.ts` / Tailwind theme exists.\n\n---\n\n## Roll-up\n\n| Action | Count | What earns it |\n|---|---:|---|\n| Block | 0 | No high-severity findings; max agent_risk 0.62 |\n| Warn | 9 | 4× dead-code blocks, 1× magic literal, 1× duplicate shape, 2× status-check drift, 1× `new Date()` in server action |\n| Ignore | 64 | 40× tutorial-fixture duplicates, 6× tiny dead-code, 2× `formatDateToLocal` clock reads, 2× known-good deep imports, 8× tokens-not-established, plus 6 boundary-line dupes inside `final ↔ starter` |\n\nThe headline for the PR author: **the policy-drift findings (`magic_domain_literal_scatter` + `duplicated_role_status_plan_check`) are the ones worth fixing**; everything else is either fixture-shaped noise or below the bar.",
