/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/refactor-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# Top 3 changes to `src/billing.ts`\n\n## 1. Split `generateInvoice` and encode the prose rule on `calculateRefundPreview`\n\n**Findings:** `crime_00001` (God Function, severity 0.9, agent_risk 0.63), plus the connected `crime_00013` (God File, 310 lines — `generateInvoice` is 204 of them) and `crime_00014` (Logic in the Alibi @ L39).\n\n`generateInvoice` is 3.4× the 60-line domain threshold (lines 50–253). An agent editing one section will routinely miss interactions in another — that's exactly what the agent_risk score is flagging. Extracting cohesive helpers (line-item assembly, tax/discount, persistence, side-effects) also shrinks the file below the 300-line God File threshold for free, so two findings collapse with one refactor.\n\nWhile you're in there: the `// Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves.` comment at L39 is a prose rule with no enforcement nearby. Encode it as a typed guard (`assertCanRefund(actor, plan)`) so the rule travels with the code, not the comment.\n\n## 2. Rename or split `calculateRefundPreview`\n\n**Finding:** `crime_00010` (False Identity, agent_risk 0.52, lines 40–44).\n\nThe `calculate…Preview` prefix promises a pure read, but the body calls `saveRefundAudit` and `sendRefundEmail`. That's the worst kind of misleading surface for agents — they will call it speculatively to \"see what would happen\" and ship audit rows + customer emails as a side effect. Either:\n\n- Rename to `processRefund` / `issueRefundAndNotify` so the side effects are disclosed, **or**\n- Extract a pure `computeRefundAmount(...)` (the actual preview) and leave the side-effecting wrapper named honestly.\n\nThis is a small edit with outsized risk reduction because the misleading name is the load-bearing failure mode.\n\n## 3. Inject a clock to eliminate direct `Date` use\n\n**Findings:** `crime_00006` (Temporal Recklessness in billing.ts, 7 direct calls across lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273), interacting with `crime_00008` (the existing `billing.test.ts` has zero asserts).\n\nFive `Date.now()` and two `new Date()` calls inside invoice generation mean every test has to monkey-patch wall time or accept flakiness. The empty test at `billing.test.ts:4-6` (\"renders the enterprise plan\", 0 expects) is almost certainly empty *because* you can't pin a moment to assert against. Inject a `Clock` (or a `now: () => Date` parameter) at the `generateInvoice` boundary, thread it through, and you unlock both deterministic tests and meaningful assertions — fixing the testability finding as a downstream effect.\n\n---\n\n**Why these three, in this order:** I ranked by `agent_risk` × interaction with other findings, not raw severity. The God Function fix dissolves the God File finding; the rename fix is the cheapest agent-risk reduction in the report; the clock fix is the prerequisite for any of the new tests you'd want to add after the split. The \"enterprise\" string sprinkle (`crime_00009`) and TODO density (`crime_00025`) are real but downstream — worth doing once the structural mess is gone.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/refactor-01-large-file.json:7:  "response": "## Split plan for `src/billing.ts`, grounded in the large_file evidence\n\n### What the `large_file` finding actually says\n- `crime_00013` evidence: **310 non-empty lines**, **1.0× the 300-line threshold**, **5 top-level exports**. We're sitting right on the threshold, so the bar isn't \"shrink dramatically\" — it's \"give each responsibility a home so the next edit doesn't push it over.\"\n- The neighbouring findings on the same file tell us *where* the responsibility boundaries already are:\n  - `large_function generateInvoice` (`crime_00001`, lines 50–253) — **204 of the 310 lines, ~66% of the file** — is the dominant blob. Splitting this alone moves the file well under threshold.\n  - `name_behavior_mismatch calculateRefundPreview` (`crime_00010`, lines 40–44) belongs to a refund flow, not invoice generation.\n  - `logic_in_comments` (`crime_00014`, line 39): \"Only owners can refund enterprise plans unless billing support approves\" sits orphaned above the refund function — a homeless rule.\n  - `direct_date` cluster (`crime_00006`, lines 57, 63, 92, 198, 238, 250, 273) is entirely inside `generateInvoice`. Splitting surfaces natural clock-injection seams per helper.\n  - `todo_density` (`crime_00025`, lines 183–308) concentrates in the audit/email/retry tail of `generateInvoice` plus the stub `listRecentInvoices`.\n\n### Caller blast radius\nGreped the whole fixture for imports of `./billing` and for the five export names. **Zero external callers** — even `src/billing.test.ts` doesn't reference the exports by name (which is the `crime_00008` / `crime_00021` weak-test problem). So this is an internal-only move; we can keep `src/billing.ts` as a thin barrel re-export and not touch any consumer.\n\n### Proposed file layout (`src/billing/` directory)\n\n| New file | What moves in | Why this boundary |\n|---|---|---|\n| `src/billing/types.ts` | `User`, `InvoiceLine`, `Invoice` interfaces (lines 4–31) | Pure types — the only thing every other split needs. Zero behaviour. |\n| `src/billing/pricing.ts` | Pure helpers extracted from `generateInvoice`: `applyPlanDiscount` (66–89), `loyaltyDiscount` (91–103), `resolvePromo` (105–126), `scoreFraudRisk` (128–143), `currencyFor` (159–165), **and the existing `tax()` function (255–268)** | The \"compute\" side. Lets us **delete the duplicate tax block inside `generateInvoice` (145–156)** — the very duplication the comment at line 145 admits to. |\n| `src/billing/refund.ts` | `calculateRefundPreview` (40–44), renamed `processRefundPreview` per the `False Identity` finding, plus a new `assertCanRefund(user, invoice)` guard that encodes the line-39 prose rule | Pulls refund out of the invoice file *and* resolves `crime_00010` + `crime_00014` in the same move. |\n| `src/billing/invoice.ts` | `generateInvoice` orchestrator (~40 lines after extraction) plus the I/O helpers: `logInvoiceAudit` (182–199), `emitInvoiceMetrics` (201–211), `renderInvoiceEmail` (213–233), `sendInvoiceEmailWithRetry` (235–250) | What remains of `generateInvoice` after the pure helpers leave is orchestration + side effects. Co-located so the clock and retry loop have one obvious place to evolve. |\n| `src/billing/recommendations.ts` | `recommendUpgrade` (272–305) | Has nothing to do with invoicing — it's a marketing/upsell helper that happens to share `User`. The deeply-nested branches need their own home before they grow. |\n| `src/billing/queries.ts` | `listRecentInvoices` stub (307–310) | Will become a DB query (per the TODO). Splitting now means the DB dependency doesn't drag invoice-generation tests into a slow lane later. |\n| `src/billing.ts` (kept) | `export * from \"./billing/types\"; export * from \"./billing/pricing\"; ...` | Barrel re-export. Zero caller churn — and we already verified there are no external imports today. |\n\n### Execution order (safest → riskiest)\n\n1. **Extract `types.ts`.** No behaviour change. Type-check should be green after the imports update inside `billing.ts`.\n2. **Extract `pricing.ts` and collapse the duplicate tax table.** This kills the `// Duplicated tax logic` comment on line 255 and the inline copy on lines 145–156 in the same move. Re-run `crimes scan` — `large_function` line range should shrink, `direct_date` count in this file should drop (the `Date.now()` at line 92 leaves with `loyaltyDiscount`).\n3. **Extract `refund.ts` and encode the comment rule.** Rename `calculateRefundPreview` → `processRefundPreview` and add the `assertCanRefund` guard. Clears `crime_00010` and `crime_00014`.\n4. **Extract `recommendations.ts` and `queries.ts`.** Single-function moves, trivially mechanical.\n5. **What's left in `invoice.ts`** is the orchestrator + four side-effect helpers (`logInvoiceAudit`, `emitInvoiceMetrics`, `renderInvoiceEmail`, `sendInvoiceEmailWithRetry`). Extract those inside the same file as a single follow-up commit — that's where the remaining clock seams live and where the `console.log` PII (FIXME at line 183) gets addressed properly.\n6. **Convert `src/billing.ts` to a barrel** so no caller — current or future — breaks.\n\n### Caller updates\n\n- **External consumers: none.** Confirmed by grep — no `from \"./billing\"` anywhere, no usages of the five export names outside the file itself.\n- **`src/billing.test.ts`** doesn't reference the exports either today (which is the separate weak-test finding). If/when we strengthen those tests, they'd import from `src/billing` (the barrel) or directly from the split files — both options work.\n- **`src/routes/settings/billing.tsx`** is flagged by `context` as related but only by domain token; it doesn't import this file.\n\n### Post-edit gate\n\nAfter step 2, re-run `crimes scan src/billing.ts --format json` and check:\n- `large_file` (`crime_00013`) gone — file should be ~50 lines as a barrel.\n- `large_function generateInvoice` line range shrinks dramatically.\n- `direct_date` count in `billing.ts` drops to whatever stays in the orchestrator.\n- A new `large_file` should **not** appear on any of the new split files (each is well under threshold by design — pricing.ts will be the largest at ~80 lines including the consolidated tax).\n\nThe split is justified by the evidence, not by feel: 66% of the file is one function, that function's own sections map to the helpers we're extracting, and an orphaned authorization rule + a name/behaviour mismatch tell us where the second module boundary belongs.",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/codex/refactor-08-architecture.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b11-561a-7b71-b862-1f4ec4feff69\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The scan has two architecture/package-surface findings relevant to this refactor:\\n\\n1. `crime_00002` — `layer_violation`\\n   - File: `src/domain/billing.ts`\\n   - Bad edge: `src/domain/billing.ts` imports `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`\\n   - Rule violated: `domain cannotImport presentation`\\n\\n2. `crime_00003` — `deep_import`\\n   - File: `src/application/billing-flow.ts`\\n   - Bad edge: imports `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`\\n   - Problem: reaches past `some-pkg`’s published public surface into private internals.\\n\\nRecommended refactor:\\n\\n- Break the import from `src/domain/billing.ts` to `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts`.\\n  Tie-in: fixes `crime_00002` and likely helps break the circular dependency in `crime_00001`.\\n\\n  The domain layer should not know how invoices are rendered. If `billing.ts` needs something from presentation, that dependency should be inverted. Put a domain-owned interface or value type in `src/domain`, for example:\\n\\n  ```ts\\n  export interface InvoicePresenter {\\n    renderInvoice(invoice: Invoice): string;\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n  Then `src/presentation/invoice-view.ts` can implement or adapt to that interface, while application code wires them together. The dependency direction becomes:\\n\\n  ```text\\n  domain <- application -> presentation\\n  ```\\n\\n  instead of:\\n\\n  ```text\\n  domain -> presentation\\n  ```\\n\\n- Redirect `src/application/billing-flow.ts` away from `some-pkg/dist/internal/private/helper.js`.\\n  Tie-in: fixes `crime_00003`.\\n\\n  Prefer the package’s public entry point, for example:\\n\\n  ```ts\\n  import { helper } from \\\"some-pkg\\\";\\n  ```\\n\\n  If the helper is not publicly exported, do not keep the deep import as a shortcut. Wrap the needed behavior behind an application-owned interface and implementation, or replace it with supported public API behavior. If this is truly missing upstream functionality, the right long-term move is an upstream export/request, not coupling to `dist/internal/private`.\\n\\nHow the risks differ:\\n\\n- `layer_violation` is architecture risk. It tells an agent that changing one layer may unintentionally require knowledge of another layer’s responsibilities. Here, domain depending on presentation inverts the intended direction of change and contributes to the 3-file cycle involving `billing-flow.ts`, `billing.ts`, and `invoice-view.ts`.\\n\\n- `deep_import` is package-boundary risk. It may work today, but it depends on private file layout inside a dependency. An agent may assume the import is stable because TypeScript resolves it, but an upgrade or rebuild of `some-pkg` can silently remove or move that path.\\n\\nSo: break the domain-to-presentation import through a domain-owned interface, and redirect the package deep import through `some-pkg`’s public API or a local adapter.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":18281,\"cached_input_tokens\":11136,\"output_tokens\":651,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":38}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/codex/review-02-react-dashboard.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b13-347c-7ce3-aff9-ecbec6bcd34d\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"No **block merge** findings here. None are `high`, and the highest `scores.agent_risk` in this petty/single-file set is `0.61`, so these are cleanup or drift-prevention items, not merge stoppers.\\n\\n**commented_out_code**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00047` `dashboard/starter-example/app/query/route.ts:21-25` | warn | medium / 0.61 | Disabled `try/catch/await/return` block can mislead future edits. |\\n| `crime_00048` `latest-invoices.tsx:19-56` | warn | medium / 0.61 | Large 38-line disabled JSX block. Worth cleaning before it gets copied. |\\n| `crime_00049` `revenue-chart.tsx:33-62` | warn | medium / 0.61 | Large commented implementation fragment. |\\n| `crime_00050` `pagination.tsx:17-50` | warn | medium / 0.61 | Disabled pagination logic is easy to revive incorrectly. |\\n| `crime_00058` `query/route.ts:5-11` | ignore | low / 0.51 | Small starter snippet; cleanup is fine but not merge-relevant. |\\n| `crime_00059` `revenue-chart.tsx:22-24` | ignore | low / 0.51 | Tiny disabled guard. |\\n| `crime_00060` `final-example/app/lib/data.ts:19-20` | ignore | low / 0.50 | Commented logging/debug delay only. |\\n| `crime_00061` `starter-example/app/lib/data.ts:19-20` | ignore | low / 0.50 | Same low-risk debug snippet. |\\n| `crime_00064` `final-example/app/query/route.ts:17-20` | ignore | low / 0.49 | Short commented response example. |\\n| `crime_00065` `starter-example/app/ui/dashboard/cards.tsx:21-28` | ignore | low / 0.49 | Small commented UI fragment. |\\n\\n**magic_domain_literal_scatter**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00051` literal `\\\"status\\\"` across invoice forms/actions | warn | medium / 0.60 | Repeated domain field names can drift, but this is still ordinary form/action wiring. Centralize when touching invoice status work. |\\n\\n**duplicated_role_status_plan_check**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00053` literal `\\\"pending\\\"` checks | warn | medium / 0.57 | Repeated status policy in edit form and badge rendering. Not blocking, but drift-prone. |\\n| `crime_00054` literal `\\\"paid\\\"` checks | warn | medium / 0.57 | Same issue for paid status. Extract constants or a status helper when editing this area. |\\n\\n**duplicate_component_shape**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00052` repeated invoice form button/action `<div>` | warn | medium / 0.57 | Repeated UI shape across create/edit forms. Worth extracting if forms keep changing; not a blocker. |\\n\\n**direct_date**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00055` `actions.ts:57` | ignore | low / 0.51 | `new Date()` for invoice action timestamp is expected app behavior unless deterministic tests are being added. |\\n| `crime_00056` `final-example/app/lib/utils.ts:14` | ignore | low / 0.51 | Date formatting helper using current locale/date behavior is low risk. |\\n| `crime_00057` `starter-example/app/lib/utils.ts:14` | ignore | low / 0.51 | Same low-risk utility usage. |\\n\\n**deep_import**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00062` `seo/components/CodeSampleModal.js` | ignore | low / 0.50 | Deep import is upgrade-fragile but isolated to demo syntax highlighting. |\\n| `crime_00063` `seo/demo/components/CodeSampleModal.js` | ignore | low / 0.50 | Same isolated dependency detail. |\\n\\n**design_token_escape**\\n\\n| Finding | Category | Severity / agent_risk | Why |\\n|---|---:|---:|---|\\n| `crime_00066`-`crime_00073` | ignore | low / 0.48 | Raw `px` values in forms/login/skeletons are style debt. Fine to fix opportunistically, not a PR gate. |\\n\\nSummary: **block merge: 0**, **warn: 8 findings**, **ignore: 19 findings**. The warnings are the medium-severity items where `agent_risk` is roughly `0.57-0.61`; everything low-severity at `0.48-0.51` is cleanup noise for this PR.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":40877,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":1649,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":516}}\n",
