/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/codex/bugfix-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e3b0b-fcd4-73a2-9c41-3684b3f4a2f4\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Most likely cause: **direct wall-clock reads in billing/date logic**, especially `src/billing.ts` finding `crime_00006`.\\n\\nThe date-boundary flakiness is probably coming from `generateInvoice` reading `Date.now()` / `new Date()` multiple times during one invoice calculation:\\n\\n- `src/billing.ts`: 5× `Date.now()`, 2× `new Date()`\\n- `src/date.ts`: additional direct date usage, mixed UTC/local access, unsafe parsing, and DST-naive day math\\n\\nAt a boundary like midnight, month end, billing-cycle rollover, or DST transition, different calls can observe different effective “days” or interpret them differently. The highest-risk supporting clue is `src/date.ts` finding `crime_00003`: the same date receiver mixes UTC and local methods, so behavior can change by host timezone.\\n\\nProposed fix:\\n\\n1. Inject a clock into billing/domain code instead of calling `Date.now()` or `new Date()` directly.\\n2. Capture `now` once at the start of `generateInvoice`.\\n3. Use one date family consistently, preferably UTC for billing calculations.\\n4. Update tests to pass a fixed boundary timestamp.\\n\\nExample shape:\\n\\n```ts\\ntype Clock = {\\n  now(): Date;\\n};\\n\\nconst systemClock: Clock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(),\\n};\\n\\nexport function generateInvoice(input: InvoiceInput, clock: Clock = systemClock) {\\n  const now = clock.now();\\n\\n  // all billing-cycle, due-date, and invoice-date logic derives from `now`\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen test the edge case with a pinned instant:\\n\\n```ts\\nconst fixedClock = {\\n  now: () => new Date(\\\"2026-03-01T00:00:00.000Z\\\"),\\n};\\n\\nconst invoice = generateInvoice(input, fixedClock);\\n\\nexpect(invoice.billingPeriodStart).toBe(\\\"...\\\");\\n```\\n\\nI would fix `src/billing.ts` first, because it directly owns invoice generation and has repeated runtime clock reads inside a large function. Then audit the helpers in `src/date.ts` for UTC/local mixing and timezone-unsafe parsing, since those can keep the boundary bug alive even after the billing clock is injected.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":26069,\"cached_input_tokens\":12160,\"output_tokens\":486,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":36}}\n",
/Users/andrew/dev/crimes-release-a/evals/results/0.7.8/claude/review-01-messy-ts-app.json:7:  "response": "# PR Review: 27 findings, 3 categories\n\nThreshold I'm using:\n- **Block** — severity high, or a latent correctness bug (timezone/temporal) the diff introduces\n- **Warn** — medium severity / `agent_risk ≥ 0.50` that signals real risk but is fixable in follow-up\n- **Ignore** — low severity, low `agent_risk`, stylistic noise, or speculative orphans\n\n## Block merge (4)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk | Why block |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00001` | God Function `generateInvoice` (204 lines) | 0.90 / 0.63 | 3.4× the domain threshold, mixes responsibilities. Any future edit lands blind to neighbouring logic — exactly the agent-edit hazard the scoring model is built around. |\n| `crime_00002` | Temporal Recklessness in `src/date.ts` (8 wall-clock reads) | 0.80 / 0.69 | High severity + `test_gap 1.0`. Domain code reading wall time with zero injectable clock is non-deterministic by construction. |\n| `crime_00003` | Half-UTC, Half-Local on the same receiver | 0.80 / 0.68 | This is the classic silent-by-host-offset bug — fails at midnight UTC on some hosts and not others, with no test catching it. Should not ship. |\n| `crime_00007` | Timezone Roulette — `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` etc. | 0.60 / 0.61 | Medium by score but I'm bumping to Block: the literals look authoritative, runtime applies host TZ silently. That's a latent bug being introduced in the diff, not just a code-health smell. |\n\n## Warn (13)\n\n| ID | Charge | sev / agent_risk | Why warn (not block) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `crime_00004` | Missing Agent Context (no AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md) | 0.60 / 0.61 | Real agent-risk uplift, but doesn't break the build or change behaviour. Track as a follow-up. |\n| `crime_00006` | Temporal Recklessness in `billing.ts` (7 calls) | 0.60 / 0.53 | Same family as `crime_00002` but billing has *some* test signal (test_gap 0.5). Fix alongside the clock-injecti